fields.english: I don't have anything before, I don't have anything behind.
fields.creole: Me no gat befo', me no got behin.'

fields.english: I don't have any biscuits in your barrel.
fields.creole: Me no gat no biscuit a-you' barrel

fields.english: I wasn't born in Ogle's back dam.
fields.creole: Me no bo'n a-Ogle back dam

fields.english: I'm telling the story as I heard it.
fields.creole: Me sell me 'tory as me buy am

fields.english: It's easier to stop a river than a woman's tongue.
fields.creole: Mo' easy fo' 'tap ribah dan woman tongue

fields.english: The longer you stay, the more your bread will burn.
fields.creole: Mo' langah you 'tan', mo' you bake-bake a-col.'

fields.english: The more men refuse, the more dinner is saved.
fields.creole: Mo' man refuse, mo' dinnah save

fields.english: More money, more sin.
fields.creole: Mo' money, mo' sin

fields.english: The more the monkey climbs, the more he shows his tail.
fields.creole: Mo' monkey climb, mo' he show he tail

fields.english: When money is gone, friends are gone.
fields.creole: Money done, frien' done

fields.english: Money doesn't grow on trees.
fields.creole: Money na a-grow 'pon tree

fields.english: Money doesn't make the man.
fields.creole: Money na mek man

fields.english: The monkey knows which tree it's climbing on.
fields.creole: Monkey know wha' tree he a-climb 'pon

fields.english: The monkey made his child, he made it so that it would spoil him.
fields.creole: Monkey mek he picknie, he mek ama teh 'e 'pile am

fields.english: Monkey says his child's eye will go deep deep.
fields.creole: Monkey men' 'e chil' eye teh 'e go deep deep

fields.english: If the father monkey jumps, the mother monkey jumps, the baby monkey must also jump.
fields.creole: Monkey papa jump, monkey mamma jump, monkey picknie mus' jump

fields.english: The monkey plays the fiddle for the baboon to run a race.
fields.creole: Monkey play fiddle fo' de baboon run race

fields.english: The monkey put his head in the salmon pot, he says the world goes round.
fields.creole: Monkey put he head a-salmon pat, he say de worl' go roun'

fields.english: The monkey says "What's in my belly is mine, what's in my mouth is what the jackman wants."
fields.creole: Monkey say "Wha' deh a-me belly a-me own, wha' deh a-me mout' a jackman want

fields.english: The monkey takes trouble from the bush and brings it home.
fields.creole: Monkey tek trouble a-bush bring am a-house

fields.english: When the monkey becomes rich, he roasts butter on a stick.
fields.creole: Monkey tu'n rich, he roas' buttah 'pon 'tick

fields.english: The moon and the star are neighbors.
fields.creole: Moon an' 'tar a-neighbour

fields.english: The moon is running, but the day will catch it.
fields.creole: Moon a-run, but day a-ketch am

fields.english: More rain, more rest
fields.creole: Mo' rain, mo' rest

fields.english: Mouth is a freeman, hand is a slave.
fields.creole: Mout' a freeman, han' a slabe

fields.english: The mouth makes it, somewhere else pays for it.
fields.creole: Mout' a-mek am, someweh else a-pay fo' am

fields.english: A mouth that cuts trousers can't fit the master.
fields.creole: Mout' cut trouses can't fit massa

fields.english: What the mouth consumes, the back suffers for.
fields.creole: Mout' eat, back pay

fields.english: I'm not the first one to tell Matty that his skin is black.
fields.creole: Na a fus' wan to tell matty he 'kin black

fields.english: Not everyone who goes to church, goes to pray.
fields.creole: Na all a-go a-chu'ch house, a-go fo' pray

fields.english: Not every dog that plays with you has your best interest at heart.
fields.creole: Na all daag wah play wid you gat you good a-he min'

fields.english: Not every horse that takes the lead initially wins the race.
fields.creole: Na all haas wah get fus' jump a-win race

fields.english: Not everyone who is courting gets married.
fields.creole: Na all man a-cou'tin' a-married

fields.english: Not every man who wears trousers is a man.
fields.creole: Na all man a-wear trouses a man

fields.english: Not all water that comes from the eye is tears.
fields.creole: Na all watah wah come out a-yeye a-cry

fields.english: Don't curse the snake before you go into the bush.
fields.creole: Na cuss snake befo' you walk a-bush

fields.english: Don't curse the water spirit when you go to the creek.
fields.creole: Na cuss watah mamma w'en you go a-creek

fields.english: Don't cast your eyes on me.
fields.creole: Na cut you' yeye 'pon me

fields.english: Don't cut your nose to spite your face.
fields.creole: Na cut you' nose fo' pile you' face

fields.english: It's the lack of a tongue that makes a cow unable to talk.
fields.creole: Na de lacking ob a tongue mek cow can't talk

fields.english: Don't dirty the water where you drink from.
fields.creole: Na dutty de pon' weh you dip you' watah

fields.english: Not every big head has sense.
fields.creole: Na ebery big head gat sense

fields.english: Not every man who says "Good night," sleeps together.
fields.creole: Na ebery man wah say "Goo' night," a-sleep togeddah

fields.english: Not everything that goes to the market is for sale.
fields.creole: Na eberyt'ing wah go a market fo' sell

fields.english: Not everything that has sugar is sweet.
fields.creole: Na eberyt'ing wah gat sugah a-sweet

fields.english: Not everything you see, should be spoken about.
fields.creole: Na eberyt'ing you see, mout' fo' talk

fields.english: Don't consider yourself a large barrel, when a butter keg can hold you.
fields.creole: Na fo'co youse'f a big puncheon, when buttah keg can hol' you

fields.english: It's not for lack of fire that peas take long to boil.
fields.creole: Na fo want ob fiah mek peas 'tan' lang fo bile

fields.english: It's not good to heat your neighbor's chair too much.
fields.creole: Na good fo' hot you matty chair too much

fields.english: Don't poke a stick in your friend's eye, or someone else will do it to you.
fields.creole: Na jook 'tick a-you matty yeye, no so somebody else go jook a-fo' you

fields.english: Don't let today spoil tomorrow.
fields.creole: Na leh to-day 'pile to-morrow

fields.english: Don't let the moonlight deceive you, and don't disrespect the dark night.
fields.creole: Na mek moonlight fool you, an' gie dark night saucy

fields.english: Don't let a full stomach fool you.
fields.creole: Na mek wan belly-full fool you

fields.english: Don't let sweet talk fool you.
fields.creole: Na mek sweet mout' fool you

fields.english: Don't let your eyes be bigger than your head.
fields.creole: Na mek you' aez pass you' head

fields.english: Not only monkeys make trousers and find they can't fit them.
fields.creole: Na monkey 'lone does mek trouses, and fin' he can't fit am

fields.english: Only a thief's dog barks at him.
fields.creole: Na only tief man daag bark 'pon

fields.english: Don't spread the tablecloth before the pot is done boiling.
fields.creole: Na 'pread table clot' befo' pat done bile

fields.english: Don't wear a long coat and smoke a cigar when you go to a water mamma dance.
fields.creole: Na put on long coat an' smoke cigah when you go a-watah mamma dance

fields.english: Don't put on Sunday clothes on a weekday.
fields.creole: Na put on Sunday clo'es 'pon week-a-day 'kin

fields.english: Don't put your hand in another person's saucepan.
fields.creole: Na shub you' han' a-matty saucepan

fields.english: Don't stop to roll up your stockings when you're running for the train.
fields.creole: Na 'tap fo' roll up 'tackin' when you a-run fo' train

fields.english: Don't judge people by their appearance.
fields.creole: No tek man by dem look

fields.english: Don't use me as your scapegoat.
fields.creole: Na tek me mek you' coo-coo pat

fields.english: Don't remove your guts and replace them with straw.
fields.creole: Na tek out you guts and put in 'traw

fields.english: Don't be embarrassed to shake hands with a poor person.
fields.creole: Na tek shame face shake cuckaba niggah han'

fields.english: Don't take your neighbor's eye to sleep with.
fields.creole: Na tek you matty yeye fo' sleep wid

fields.english: Don't throw away dirty water until you get clean.
fields.creole: Na t'row 'way dutty watah teh you get clean

fields.english: There's a dog named Pompey.
fields.creole: Na wan daag name Pompey

fields.english: Nancy doesn't like to catch marabunta (a type of ant) because it has a long sting.
fields.creole: Nancy no like fo' ketch marabuntah 'cause he gat lang 'ting

fields.english: Never is the day a canoe sinks at the shore.
fields.creole: Nebbah de day canoe bore punt

fields.english: Never eat crab-back and drink water.
fields.creole: Nebbah eat crab-back an' drink watah

fields.english: Never go at night to buy black cloth at the store.
fields.creole: Nebbah go a-night fo' buy black clat' a-'tore

fields.english: Never mind, it's why the estate doesn't have a back road.
fields.creole: Nebbah min'" mek estate no gat back-dam

fields.english: Never put out fire to fury
fields.creole: Nebbah out fiah to fury

fields.english: Never sell everything as you buy it.
fields.creole: Nebbah sell eberyt'ing as you buy am

fields.english: Never put your head where you know you can't get out.
fields.creole: Nebbah shub you' head weh you know you go fasten

fields.english: Never look for trouble until trouble comes to you.
fields.creole: Nebbah trouble trouble till trouble trouble you

fields.english: Never throw away today what you will want tomorrow.
fields.creole: Nebbah t'row 'way to-day wha' you go want to-morrow

fields.english: Never throw away your walking stick until you cross the river.
fields.creole: Nebbah t'row 'way you walking 'tiek teh you cross ribah

fields.english: Never try to make H turn into K.
fields.creole: Nebbah you try fo' mek H tu'n K

fields.english: As one person tries to rise, his fellow man pulls him down.
fields.creole: Niggah a-climb up, he matty a-pull he down

fields.english: The black man forgets, the white man remembers.
fields.creole: Niggah fo'get, Bacra 'membah

fields.english: The black man lives happily, he would greet the governor "good morning".
fields.creole: Niggah libe happy, he go tell gubnah "ma'nin'

fields.english: The black man says, "Wait first"; The Portuguese says, "Especially".
fields.creole: Niggah say, "Wait fus"; Potagee say, "Specalah

fields.english: The quality of the barrel doesn't improve the quality of the herring.
fields.creole: No bettah de barrel, no bettah de herrin'

fields.english: Nobody will beg when rain is coming.
fields.creole: Nobody go beg w'en rain da come

fields.english: Noise at the market doesn't mean it's a selling day.
fields.creole: Noise a-market no selling day

fields.english: If you don't catch it, you don't have it.
fields.creole: No ketchee, no habee

fields.english: No longer fiddle, no longer dance
fields.creole: No langah fiddle, no langah dance

fields.english: When a window isn't good, it makes a lot of noise when the wind blows.
fields.creole: When windah na good, 'e mek 'nough noise a-win'

fields.english: A foolish man uses a fork to eat soup.
fields.creole: Nonsense man tek fark fo' nyam soup

fields.english: No trick, no living.
fields.creole: No trick no libin'

fields.english: Now it's mango season; people can't sit still, they're always eating.
fields.creole: Now a mango season; matty no a-si' down matty doo' mout'

fields.english: Eat some, leave some for tomorrow.
fields.creole: Nyam some, lef' some fo' to-morrow

fields.english: Okra and cassava can't make soup in the same pot.
fields.creole: Ochro an' cassava can't mek soup a-wan pat

fields.english: An old fire-stick catches fire quickly.
fields.creole: Ol' fiah-'tick soon ketch

fields.english: Old grandmother swore at the caterpillar; the caterpillar swore to work his belly.
fields.creole: Ol' granny sweah fo' catapillah; catapillah sweah fo' wo'k he belly

fields.english: Old grudges make the bat lay eggs.
fields.creole: Ol' grudge mek bat lay egg

fields.english: Old grudges, new beatings
fields.creole: Ol' grudge, new licks

fields.english: Father works, child spends.
fields.creole: Faada wo'k picknie spen'

fields.english: Family conflicts don't cut deep.
fields.creole: Family cutlish na cut deep

fields.english: Pluck the fat chicken clean.
fields.creole: Fat fowl, pick am clean

fields.english: A long journey makes the okra dry on the tree.
fields.creole: Far-a-pa mek ochro dry a-tree

fields.english: Feast today, famine tomorrow
fields.creole: Feast to-day, famine to-morrow

fields.english: Fire and powder don't matter.
fields.creole: Fiah an' powdah no matty

fields.english: Fire is at the monkey's tail, he says "Cool breeze".
fields.creole: Fiah deh a-money tail he say "Cool breeze

fields.english: Without fire, the pot can't boil.
fields.creole: Fiah no deh, pat can't boil

fields.english: The finger never says "Look here," but "Look over there."
fields.creole: Fingah nebba say "Look yah," but "Look yandah

fields.english: The fish playing in the sea doesn't know that water is boiling for it.
fields.creole: Fish a-play a-sea, he no sabby watah a-bile fo' am

fields.english: A fisherman never says his own fish stinks.
fields.creole: Fishaman nebba say he own fish 'tink

fields.english: When the fish is asleep, its enemy cuts its tail.
fields.creole: Fish a-sleep, he matty a-cut he tail

fields.english: Don't you scratch a flea bite?
fields.creole: Flea bite, you no 'cratch?

fields.english: The fly says it's having fun, not knowing the spider is near.
fields.creole: Fly say ya pledja, he na' know spidah neah

fields.english: The fly sits down and shakes its foot, then says "There's a story before, there's a story behind."
fields.creole: Fly si' down an' shake he foot, den say "'Tory befo', 'tory behin'

fields.english: Following a pattern never leads to trouble.
fields.creole: Follow pattern nebba out ob trouble

fields.english: The pounded plantain is not for you, don't cut it deep.
fields.creole: Foo-foo na fo' you, na cut am deep

fields.english: It's for me, before me, but it's not for us.
fields.creole: Fo' me a-fo' me, but f'awe na fo' me

fields.english: A foolish man learns from a wise man's wisdom.
fields.creole: Foolish man a-learn sense man sense

fields.english: A foolish man talks, but doesn't listen.
fields.creole: Foolish man a-talk, but na a-listen

fields.english: A foolish man kills the cow, but a sensible man eats it.
fields.creole: Foolish man kill cow, sense man eat am

fields.english: A foolish man uses his fist to hammer a nail into a plank.
fields.creole: Foolish man tek cuff fo' knack nail a-plank

fields.english: The food I eat, I'm not giving you.
fields.creole: Food me eat me na gie you

fields.english: Because of this, because of this, I can't do better.
fields.creole: Fo' secka fo' secka me can't do bettah

fields.english: A chicken may hatch a duck, but it doesn't do what a duck does.
fields.creole: Fowl a-hatch duck, but he no a-do wha' duck a-do

fields.english: Chickens and ducks are not the same, but they sleep in the same pen.
fields.creole: Fowl an' duck no wan, but dem sleep a-wan pen

fields.english: The rooster may be foolish, but that doesn't make him a villain.
fields.creole: Fowl-cock a fool, but da na mek am villain

fields.english: The country of the fowl-cook has changed; man has not changed.
fields.creole: Fowl-cook country tu'n; man na tu'n

fields.english: The rooster heard that war was coming, so he climbed to the top of a tree and declared himself a lighthouse keeper.
fields.creole: Fowl-cook hear war a-come he climb a-tap tree say he a light-house keepah

fields.english: The chicken eats and wipes its beak on the ground; the dog licks the hand that feeds it.
fields.creole: Fowl eat an' wipe he mout' a-groun'; daag a-lick de han' wah feed am

fields.english: The chicken overlooks the corn, it's naughty.
fields.creole: Fowl eye pass co'n, he bad

fields.english: When the fowl gives a dance, the cockroach has no business being there.
fields.creole: Fowl gie dance, cockroach no bu'iness deh

fields.english: The chicken is happy, but the hawk catches it.
fields.creole: Fowl merry, hawk ketch am

fields.english: A hen doesn't miss her egg until she wants to sit on it.
fields.creole: Fowl no a-miss he egg teh he wan' fo' set

fields.english: The chicken says it's going to sleep early because it doesn't want trouble to find it.
fields.creole: Fowl say he a-sleep soon, 'cause he no wan' trouble fo' meet am

fields.english: The chicken sees the matapee (a long wicker sieve) and thinks it's a camoodi (a boa constrictor).
fields.creole: Fowl see matapee he say a camoodi

fields.english: When a chicken sees an ant's nest, it sharpens its claws.
fields.creole: Fowl see wood ants' nes', he sharpen he toe

fields.english: The chicken swears to hatch the rotten egg, and the rotten egg swears to spoil its skin.
fields.creole: Fowl swaer fo' hatch rotten egg, rotten egg swear fo' pile he 'kin'

fields.english: The chicken swears by its egg, not by its chick.
fields.creole: Fowl swear fo' him hegg, he no swear fo' him picknie

fields.english: A hen steps on her chicks, but she doesn't step hard.
fields.creole: Fowl tread 'pon he chicken, but he no tread haad

fields.english: What's for you is for you, what's for me is for me.
fields.creole: Fo' you a-fo you, fo' me a-fo' me

fields.english: For you and for us are not the same.
fields.creole: Fo' you an' fo' awe na wan

fields.english: A man with a full belly doesn't know what a hungry belly suffers.
fields.creole: Full belly man na know wha' hungry belly a-suffer

fields.english: The first jump is not a jump.
fields.creole: Fus' jump na jump

fields.english: The first laugh isn't the end.
fields.creole: Fus' laugh ain't de ending

fields.english: Girl, I love you because you have long black hair.
fields.creole: Gal me lobe you 'cause you got lotan hair

fields.english: A girl who doesn't listen to her mother's advice will find her mistake.
fields.creole: Gal wah no yery mamma 'tory sa larikary (find her mistake.)

fields.english: A gambling man walks with his liver in his hand.
fields.creole: Gamble man a-walk wid he libba a-he han'

fields.english: The game that a dog can play with a snake, it can't play it with an anteater.
fields.creole: Game wah daag a-play with sal'pentah, he can't play am wid ants-eater

fields.english: Get it for nothing, eat it in excess.
fields.creole: Get am fo' not'in' eat am fo' glutton

fields.english: A penny's worth of bread won't satisfy a man's hunger, but it will fill his mouth.
fields.creole: Gill bread na a-full man yeye, but he full he mout'

fields.english: A penny bread doesn't break a little Creole's mouth.
fields.creole: Gill bread na ha tear li'l creole mout'

fields.english: The goat is going along merrily, heading towards the pound.
fields.creole: Goat a-merry, a-pung he a-go

fields.english: Goats and sheep can't stay in the same pen.
fields.creole: Goat an' sheep can't 'tan' a-wan pen

fields.english: The goat is enjoying himself, he forgets that the knife is on the table.
fields.creole: Goat a-plesha, he fo'get knife a-table

fields.english: The goat is dead, but its skin is still useful.
fields.creole: Goat dead, but he 'kin sa mek down

fields.english: The goat is across the river, it's giving the tiger attitude.
fields.creole: Goat deh obah ribah, he gie tigah saucy

fields.english: The goat's foot is broken, but its mouth is not broken.
fields.creole: Gaot foot bruck, but he mout' no bruck

fields.english: Goat fears tiger, eye fears eye
fields.creole: Goat friken tigah, yeye friken yeye

fields.english: A goat's head and a sheep's head are not the same.
fields.creole: Goat head an' sheep head na wan

fields.english: The goat knows it can jump, that's why it climbs high places.
fields.creole: Goat know he can jump da mek he does climb high place

fields.english: The goat taught its kid to climb high places, then turned back and warned it that it would break its neck if it climbed there.
fields.creole: Goat la'n he picknie fo' climb a high place, den tu'n back tell am say he go bruck he nek if he climb deh

fields.english: A goat is sitting down grazing on a rope, while the small wild animal's mother is cooking sweet soup.
fields.creole: Goat si' down a rope a-graze, yawarri mamma cook sweet soup

fields.english: Trouble and the sea have no back door.
fields.creole: Trouble an' sea no gat no back doo

fields.english: God Almighty never sleeps.
fields.creole: God A'mighty nebba sleep

fields.english: God doesn't like ugliness.
fields.creole: God no like ugly

fields.english: A gold digger's money is blind.
fields.creole: Gol' diggah money na gat yeye fo' see

fields.english: Good calabash can't float in the river.
fields.creole: Good calabash can't float a-ribah

fields.english: A good hen lays eggs, what do you think of that?
fields.creole: Good fowl 'pile egg, wha' you t'ink a sensa?

fields.english: A good heart is what makes the world stand as it is today.
fields.creole: Good heart mek haag 'tan' so t'day

fields.english: Good reputation is like an egg, once it falls you can't pick it up.
fields.creole: Good libin' 'tan' like hegg, when he fall you can't pick am up

fields.english: Good men don't last long, but bad men live forever.
fields.creole: Good man no las' lang, but bad man libe fo' true

fields.english: I do good, but I see bad.
fields.creole: Good me do, bad me see

fields.english: A good woman can make sugar cake from a cayman's teeth.
fields.creole: Good ooman tek cayman teet' mek sugah cake

fields.english: Good sir stands like a rooster wanting to crow.
fields.creole: Good sahib 'tan' like a cock wan' crow

fields.english: A good thief becomes a good watchman.
fields.creole: Good tief man tu'n good watchman

fields.english: Good words are good, but good deeds are better.
fields.creole: Good word good, good deed bettah

fields.english: Grass is growing, but the horse is starving.
fields.creole: Grass a-grow, but haas a-'tarve

fields.english: Being too greedy can lead to one's downfall.
fields.creole: Greedy choke puppy

fields.english: A greedy person always goes to bed hungry.
fields.creole: Greedy man always sleep hungry

fields.english: A greedy man's eyes turn yellow twice.
fields.creole: Greedy man yeye yalla two time

fields.english: Greedy people get angry twice.
fields.creole: Greedy people does bex two time

fields.english: The green lime dropped, leaving the yellow one.
fields.creole: Green lime drap lef' yalla wan

fields.english: The governor doesn't know what he wants until he's hungry.
fields.creole: Gubnah no know he want till he hungry

fields.english: The guinea pig says he doesn't want a story, that's why he doesn't have a tail.
fields.creole: Guinea pig say he no wan' 'tory, da da mek he no gat tail

fields.english: A gunman can't stand up to kill all birds.
fields.creole: Gun man can't 'tan' up fo' kill all bi'd

fields.english: A gun doesn't know its own master.
fields.creole: Gun no know he own massa

fields.english: The gutter is running water, but there must be a bucket to catch it.
fields.creole: Guttah a-run watah, but pail mus' deh fo' ketch am

fields.english: A hog is born with a tail, but it can live without it.
fields.creole: Haag bo'n wid tail, but he can libe widout am

fields.english: A hog can't get fat without eating its offspring.
fields.creole: Haag can't fat birout he eat he pickin'

fields.english: Hog head and hog tail are not the same.
fields.creole: Haag head an haag tail na wan

fields.english: The doctor is not available.
fields.creole: Haag na gat dactah

fields.english: A horse in the pasture is not a horse in the stable.
fields.creole: Haas a-pastah na haas a-stable

fields.english: A horse is a strong creature, but a small stick can break its back.
fields.creole: Haas a 'trang somet'ing, but li'l 'tick bruck he back

fields.english: The horse gets credit for its running speed, the donkey for its kicking one.
fields.creole: Hass get credit fo' he runnin' foot, jackass fo' he kickin wan

fields.english: Having your own is better than being beholden.
fields.creole: Hab you' own bettah dan beholden

fields.english: Hard living makes a driver carry hog meat.
fields.creole: Ha'd libin' mek dribah carry haag meat

fields.english: Hard living makes the plower and the ibis feed in the same drain.
fields.creole: Ha'd libin' mek ploward an' gaulin' a-feed a-wan drain

fields.english: Hard times make a dog eat roasted corn.
fields.creole: Ha'd time mek daag nyam roas' co'n

fields.english: Hard times make a chicken catch fish in a trench.
fields.creole: Ha'd time mek fowl ketch fish a-trench

fields.english: The old guitar plays very nice tunes.
fields.creole: Ol' guitar play bery nice chune

fields.english: Old rat eats new cheese.
fields.creole: Ol' rat eat new cheese

fields.english: Old things are bringing new ones.
fields.creole: O tings a-bring new ones

fields.english: One egg can't produce two chickens.
fields.creole: One egg can't gie two chicken

fields.english: One finger can't catch lice.

fields.english: A long-nosed dog can't blow fire.
fields.creole: Lang nose daag can't blow fiah

fields.english: The long story is that the turtle doesn't want to carry its shell on its back.
fields.creole: Lang 'tory tu'tle no wan' mek he carry he trunk a-he back

fields.english: An educated man walks carefully, an uneducated man makes noise.
fields.creole: Larnid man walk saf'ly, unlarnid man keep nise

fields.english: A lazy person always has a lot of work.
fields.creole: Lazy man always get 'nough wo'k

fields.english: A lazy man's belly is never satisfied.
fields.creole: Lazy man belly neba sa full

fields.english: When a leaf falls into the water, it doesn't rot immediately.
fields.creole: Leaf fall a-watah, he no rotten wan time

fields.english: Fewer guests, fewer dirty dishes.
fields.creole: Less company, less dutty plate

fields.english: Lies have no legs.
fields.creole: Lie hab no legs

fields.english: Lies more than fire burns.
fields.creole: Lie mo' dan fiah-bu'n

fields.english: The little boy is impressing the grown man.
fields.creole: Li'l boy a-swell big man yeye

fields.english: A little boy doesn't climb a ladder to become a big man.
fields.creole: Li'l boy na a-climb laddah fo' tu'n big man

fields.english: The little finger says "Look over there," but the thumb says "Look here."
fields.creole: Li'l fingah say "Look yandah," bing t'umb say "Look yah

fields.english: A little fun is better than a whole gun.
fields.creole: Li'l fun bettah mo' dan whole gun

fields.english: Small garden, but bitter weed
fields.creole: Li'l garden, but bittah weed

fields.english: Small shoe, big shoe, same price; give him the big shoe.
fields.creole: Li'l juta, big juta, same money; gie am big juta

fields.english: A small trench can hold a big fish.
fields.creole: Li'l trench a-hol' in big fish

fields.english: A limb can't stand without a tree.
fields.creole: Limb can't 'tan berout tree

fields.english: Lime never tastes sweet
fields.creole: Lime nebba tas'e sweet

fields.english: A free goat doesn't understand what a tied-up goat feels.
fields.creole: Loose-goat na a-feel wha' tie-goat a-feel

fields.english: Luck is better than being handsome.
fields.creole: Luck mo' bettah dan han'some

fields.english: The macaw asked the parrot if the pajarra fruit was ripe, and it replied "One, one."
fields.creole: Maccaw ask parrot pajarra ripe, he say "Wan, wan

fields.english: A man who is courting must dress well.
fields.creole: Man a-cou'tin' mus' go gay

fields.english: The manager's cow says, "The white man's work is never done."
fields.creole: Manaja cow say, "Bacra wo'k nebba done

fields.english: The manager's horse eats good oats.
fields.creole: Manaja haas nyam good oats

fields.english: The manager is withholding the coolie's money, but when the coolie is preparing for the Tadja festival, the manager is the first to open his mouth because he is participating.
fields.creole: Manaja 'tap coolie money, but when coolie mek tadja, a-manaja doo' mout' fus' he a-play

fields.english: A man always looks for what he doesn't want to see.
fields.creole: Man always look fo' wha' he no wan' fo' see

fields.english: A man saw the monkey's neck before he put a chain around its waist.
fields.creole: Man bin see monkey neck befo' he put chain a-he waist

fields.english: A man bought a big-bellied horse, he wants it to cut grass.
fields.creole: Man buy big belly haas, he wan ha' fo cut grass

fields.english: A man can't do better; he says "No matter".
fields.creole: Man can't do bettah; he say "No mattah

fields.english: A man can't get the pamawarri (a prickly bush rope) if he's afraid that its thorns will prick him.
fields.creole: Man can't get pamawarri if he friken he pimplah go chook am

fields.english: A man can run, but a man can't hide.
fields.creole: Man can run, but man can't hide

fields.english: A man cuts his timber so he can haul it.
fields.creole: Man cut he timbah sa haul am

fields.english: When a man dies, grass grows at his door.
fields.creole: Man dead, grass grow a-he doo'

fields.english: When a man dies, he is truly dead.
fields.creole: Man die, he die fo' true

fields.english: After the meal is cooked, the spoon is the last thing to be used.
fields.creole: Man done cook, spoon las'

fields.english: If the man is drunk and the woman is drunk, who will close the door?
fields.creole: Man drunk, ooman drunk, who fo' shut de doo'

fields.english: A man with manners, he has a lot of pounded plantain.
fields.creole: Man gat mannas, he get big foofoo

fields.english: A man may be smart, but a horse can still kick him.
fields.creole: Man gat sense, but haas can kick am

fields.english: If a man talks too much, he will pay for his father's mistakes.
fields.creole: Man gat too much tongue, he pay he daddy debt

fields.english: A man has two houses, yet he sleeps hungry.
fields.creole: Man gat two 'ouse, he sleep hungry

fields.english: A man has two eyes, but can't look in two places at once.
fields.creole: Man gat two yeye, but can't look a-two place

fields.english: A man's hand makes twine, but the twine turns back to tie his hand.
fields.creole: Man han' a-mek twine, but twine a-tu'n back tie he han'

fields.english: A bad name in the morning is better than one in the afternoon.
fields.creole: Ma'nin' bad name bettah mo' 'an aftanoon wan

fields.english: When a man hits iron, the iron doesn't feel it, but when iron hits a man, the man feels it.
fields.creole: Man knack iron, iron na a-feel am, iron knack man, man a-feel am

fields.english: A man knows his weakness, he refuses the challenge of a strong man.
fields.creole: Man know he weak, he refuse 'trang man challenge

fields.english: People may know your face, but they don't know your heart.
fields.creole: Man know you' face, but he na know you' haat

fields.english: A man makes a coffin, but he doesn't want to go there.
fields.creole: Man mek coffin, but he no like a-go deh

fields.english: One must pay to gain wisdom.
fields.creole: Man mus' pay fo' larn sense

fields.english: A man must see his wife first before he buys a bed.
fields.creole: Man mus' see he wife fus' befo' he buy bed

fields.english: A man is not a thief until the watchman catches him.
fields.creole: Man na a tief teh watchman ketch am

fields.english: A man doesn't know what trouble is, until he has too much trouble.
fields.creole: Man na know a trouble, but he know too much a trouble

fields.english: A man doesn't appreciate his mother until she is dead.
fields.creole: Man na know he mamma use teh he dead

fields.english: A man's dreams are not over until he is done sleeping.
fields.creole: Man no done sleep, he no done dream

fields.english: If a man doesn't have feet, he can't walk.
fields.creole: Man no gat foot, he can't walk

fields.english: If a man doesn't like you, he'll give you a basket to fetch water.
fields.creole: Man no like you, he gie you basket fo' fetch watah

fields.english: If a man is not accustomed to chocolate, he says he won't drink it.
fields.creole: Man no nuse (used to) chacklit, he say he no a drink am

fields.english: If a man doesn't speak, news can't spread.
fields.creole: Man no talk, news can't go

fields.english: When a man is satisfied, he stops eating.
fields.creole: Man satisfy, he bore pat

fields.english: A man sees a calabash, but he doesn't know what's inside.
fields.creole: Man see gooby, but he na know wha' deh inside

fields.english: If a man talks too much, he pays his father's debt.
fields.creole: Man talk too much, he pay he daddy debt

fields.english: A man who starts before he's ready won't achieve good results.
fields.creole: Man 'tart befo' he ready can't meet good

fields.english: A man can predict his friend's fortune, but can't predict his own.
fields.creole: Man tell he matty farchin, but can't tell he own

fields.english: A man takes care of his own bed, he doesn't care about it because it's true, his neighbor cares for it for him.
fields.creole: Man tek row a-dam bed he na care am true, he matty care am fo❜ am

fields.english: If a man wants to drink rum, he says you should taste brandy to give him an appetite.
fields.creole: Man wan' fo' drink rum, he say yah tas'e brandy fo' gie am appetite

fields.english: A man who has a bottle on the table has many friends.
fields.creole: Man wah got bottle a-table got plenty frien'

fields.english: A man who wants to learn, will not find it hard to find a chapter.
fields.creole: Man wah know book, na haad fo' fin' chaptah

fields.english: A man without sense is like a bucket without a bottom.
fields.creole: Man wah na gat sense 'tan' like bucket berout battam

fields.english: A man who wants two wives must have two tongues.
fields.creole: Man wah wan' two wife mus' hab two tongue

fields.english: A man's weapon is his fist, a woman's weapon is her tongue.
fields.creole: Man weapon a-he fist, woman weapon a-he tongue

fields.english: A sensible man won't put his head in a hole.
fields.creole: Man wid sense na go shub he head a-hole

fields.english: The Marabunta (a type of ant) can bite, but it can't bite a spider.
fields.creole: Marabuntah a bite, but he can't bite nancy

fields.english: Being married doesn't guarantee that he is stable.
fields.creole: Married na sure he gat foot

fields.english: Marriage has teeth, it bites like a crab.
fields.creole: Married gat teet', he bite like crab

fields.english: There's no back door in marriage.
fields.creole: Married no got back doo.'

fields.english: Master's bull, master's cow
fields.creole: Massa bull, massa cow

fields.english: The master's servant is in a blanket.
fields.creole: Massa niggah a-blanket

fields.english: Matty lost his dog, his neighbor's corn field is full.
fields.creole: Matty loss he haag, he neighbah co'n-jah full

fields.english: Neighbor, what you want, you want to hide.
fields.creole: Matty wan you wan', you' wan you hide

fields.english: Neighbor, something sweet for you is bitter to others.
fields.creole: Matty somet'ing sweet fo you own bittah

fields.english: I am fire, I can't stand in a bag.
fields.creole: Me a fiah, me can't 'tan' a-bag

fields.english: I used to be a good dancer, but chigoe fleas ruined my foot.
fields.creole: Me bin a good dance man, but chiggah 'pile me foot

fields.english: I bought my calico, I must wear it.
fields.creole: Me buy me calico, me mus' wear am

fields.english: I'm already a dead dog, I don't care to think.
fields.creole: Me dead haag a'ready, me no ca' fo' 'tink

fields.english: The dog is skinny but its head is big.
fields.creole: Daag magah he head big

fields.english: Dog doesn't eat dog
fields.creole: Daag no nyam daag

fields.english: The dog says he keeps his dreams in his belly because he doesn't know how to talk.
fields.creole: Daag say he sa keep he dream a-he belly 'cause he no know fo' talk

fields.english: The dog set a trap to catch the hare, he fastened it himself.
fields.creole: Daag set trap fo' ketch accouri, he fasten dey hese'f

fields.english: The dog stuck his head in the salmon pot, he said he's seeing how the world goes round.
fields.creole: Daag shub he head a-salmon pat, he sa see how de world a-go roun'

fields.english: The dog trusts his feet, that's why he can be impudent to the tiger.
fields.creole: Daag trus' he foot mek he gie tigah saucy

fields.english: The dog that barks a lot runs away when it's time to bite.
fields.creole: Daag wah a-bark plenty a-run 'way time fo' bite

fields.english: The dog that brings a bone will carry it away.
fields.creole: Daag wah a-bring a bone sa, carry am

fields.english: The dog that eats what its friend left is never strong.
fields.creole: Daag wah a-eat wha' he matty lef' nebba 'trang

fields.english: A dog that is used to sucking eggs can't stop.
fields.creole: Daag wah use fo' suck egg can't lib (leave) off

fields.english: A dog walks on a dead lion.
fields.creole: Daag walk 'pon dead lion

fields.english: The dog wants to see a bonfire, so he throws grass on the fire's coals.
fields.creole: Daag wan' fo' see banfiah, he t'row grass 'pon fiah coal

fields.english: That foolish man wears a ring in his nose.
fields.creole: Da chupit man wear ring a-he nose

fields.english: That greedy person is always eating his food.
fields.creole: Da craben always a-eat a-pat

fields.english: The doctor doesn't know what's hurting you until you tell him.
fields.creole: Dactah na a-know weh a hu't you teh you tell am

fields.english: Doctor's medicine is always good.
fields.creole: Dactah physic always good

fields.english: A dainty dog will eat dirty pudding.
fields.creole: Dainty daag nyam dutty puddin'

fields.english: That lazy donkey can't carry his own oats.
fields.creole: Da lazy jackass can't carry he own oats

fields.english: The movement that rice has in a pot, it doesn't have on a plate.
fields.creole: Da motion wah rice got a-pot, he no got a-plate

fields.english: The same mouth a man uses to court a woman to bring her into his house, is the same mouth he uses to put her out the door.
fields.creole: Da mout' man tek fo cou'tin ooman fo' put am a-he house, a na da same mout' he a-tek fo' put am a-doo'

fields.english: The horse arrived at that place, and the donkey arrived safely too.
fields.creole: Da-place hass meet, safly safly jackass sa meet

fields.english: Wherever you see molasses, you're sure to see a blue fly.
fields.creole: Da place you see molasses, you sure fo' see blue fly

fields.english: The place where I live, it's really good.
fields.creole: Da place weh 1ibin', deh 'tan' foo good

fields.english: Go back to the place where the thorn pricked your foot to remove it.
fields.creole: Da place weh pimplah bore you foot, go back deh go tek am out

fields.english: Dark night has no governor.
fields.creole: Dark night hab no gubnah

fields.english: Dark night makes a fly boil soup.
fields.creole: Dark night mek fly boil a-soup

fields.english: The thing that pleases the goat is what kills it.
fields.creole: Da t'ing wah sweeten goat, a da a-kill am

fields.english: What you see in the daytime, don't use a torch to look for it at night.
fields.creole: Da somet'ing you a-see a-day time, no tek fiah 'tick a-night fo' look am

fields.english: A dead chicken brings money.
fields.creole: Dead chicken bring dallah

fields.english: Death is in the horse's eye, but he doesn't care for his master.
fields.creole: Dead deh a-hass eye, he no ca' fo' he massa

fields.english: The death is not over, the crying is not over.
fields.creole: Dead no done, cry no done

fields.english: Death seems to forget him.
fields.creole: Dead seem fo' fo'get he

fields.english: The devil tempts, but he does not force.
fields.creole: Debil a-tempt, but he no a-fo'ce

fields.english: The devil isn't bothered by the fact that he is painted black.
fields.creole: Debil bad no see he paint am black

fields.english: The longest prayer has an amen.
fields.creole: De langes' pray got a amen

fields.english: The same hammer that drives the nail in can take it out.
fields.creole: De same hammah wah dribe nail sa tek am out

fields.english: Dig a hole to fill a hole.
fields.creole: Dig a hole fo' full a hole

fields.english: This is saying one thing after another, until a story is formed.
fields.creole: Dis a-tell tarra, tara narra, till 'tory come

fields.english: Things are not like they used to be.
fields.creole: Dis time no like befo' time

fields.english: An eye for an eye is not witchcraft.
fields.creole: Do fo' do no obeah

fields.english: "Don't worry," maintain a large household.
fields.creole: Don' ca'e," keep big house

fields.english: Don't let your tail pass your head.
fields.creole: Don' mek you tail pass you head

fields.english: Don't judge my story by your own standards and weight.
fields.creole: Don' weigh me 'tory by you own 'cale an' weight

fields.english: What you do, is not what you love.
fields.creole: Do so no lobe so

fields.english: Downfall is not for one man.
fields.creole: Downfall no fo' wan man

fields.english: The driver is not playing Creole music.
fields.creole: Dribah na deh creole a-play

fields.english: Drive the yellow cow, the black one must run.
fields.creole: Dribe yalla cow, black wan mus' run

fields.english: Drink rum in your mouth, it says fly in your head.
fields.creole: Drink rum a-you mout', he sa f1y a-you head

fields.english: A drunk man never knows he's drunk.
fields.creole: Drunk man nebba know he drunk

fields.english: A drunk man says to a lamp post, "Excuse me, sir."
fields.creole: Drunk man tell lantern pos', "ask paadon, sah

fields.english: Dry wood is burning and green wood is burning too.
fields.creole: Dry wood a-bu'n an' green wood a-bu'n too

fields.english: The duck has water to wash its skin, the chicken wants it to drink.
fields.creole: Duck hab watah fo' was' he 'kin, fowl want am fo' drink

fields.english: Dirty water can put out fire.
fields.creole: Dutty watah can out fiah

fields.english: Dirty water cools the kettle
fields.creole: Dutty watah cool cappah

fields.english: What the ear doesn't hear, the eye will see.
fields.creole: Ear no yery, yeye sa see

fields.english: Easy come, easy go.
fields.creole: Easy get easy spen'

fields.english: What comes easily doesn't cause pain.
fields.creole: Easy squeeze no feel hurt

fields.english: Not every full belly is satisfied.
fields.creole: Ebery belly-full no a pat full

fields.english: Everyone feels their own pain.
fields.creole: Eberybody feel he own pain

fields.english: Every captain is the master of his own boat.
fields.creole: Ebery cap'n bass he own boat

fields.english: Every rooster crows at his own door, mouth.
fields.creole: Ebery cock crow a-he own doo, mout'

fields.english: Every cow cries for its own calf.
fields.creole: Ebery cow cry fo' he own calf

fields.english: Every dog is biting its master's door.
fields.creole: Ebery daag a-bite da-he massa doo'

fields.english: Every dog has its day.
fields.creole: Ebery daag ha' he day

fields.english: Every donkey thinks he's good enough to rank with the governor's horse.
fields.creole: Ebery donkey t'ink hese'f good fo' rank wid gubnah hass

fields.english: Every day the bucket goes to the well, one day its bottom will fall out.
fields.creole: Ebery day bucket go a-well, wan day he battam sa lef'

fields.english: Every day the devil helps the thief; one day God must help the watchman.
fields.creole: Ebery day debil help tief; wan day God mus' help watchman

fields.english: Every day is a fishing day, but not every day is a catching day.
fields.creole: Ebery day fishin' day, but ebery day no ketchin' day

fields.english: Every day you challenge your fellow, one day you will get your poison.
fields.creole: Ebery day you a-challenge you matty, wan day you sa get you' poison

fields.english: Every day you play in dirty water, one day it will dirty your skin.
fields.creole: Ebery day you a-play a-dutty watah, wan day he go nassy you' 'kin

fields.english: Every field must have grass.
fields.creole: Ebery fiel' mus' get grass

fields.english: Every fool has his own sense.
fields.creole: Ebery fool got he own sense

fields.english: Every grass is a man at night time.
fields.creole: Ebery grass is a man a-night time

fields.english: Not every haul of the net catches June fish.
fields.creole: Ebery haul ob de net no ketch June fish

fields.english: Not every greeting is a genuine greeting.
fields.creole: Ebery howdee na howdee

fields.english: Every vulture thinks its own offspring is white.
fields.creole: Ebery John crow t'ink he own picknie white

fields.english: Not every smile is genuine.
fields.creole: Ebery 'kin teet' no laugh

fields.english: Every long prayer must have an amen.
fields.creole: Ebery lang prayer mus' gat amen

fields.english: Every lawyer likes a fat fowl.
fields.creole: Ebery lawyer like fat fowl

fields.english: Every man knows where his own house is leaking.
fields.creole: Ebery man know weh he own house a-leak

fields.english: Every man is master of his own house.
fields.creole: Ebery man massa fo' he own house

fields.english: Every man to his own class
fields.creole: Ebery man to he own class

fields.english: Every man works for money, but not every man can keep it.
fields.creole: Ebery man wo'k fo' money, but no ebery man can keep am

fields.english: Every made up face doesn't cry.
fields.creole: Ebery mek up face na cry

fields.english: Every rope has two ends.
fields.creole: Ebery rope gat two en'

fields.english: Not every handshake is a genuine handshake.
fields.creole: Ebery shake han' no shake han'

fields.english: Not everyone who has their eyes closed is asleep.
fields.creole: Ebery shut eye na a-sleep

fields.english: Every sore eye is a watery eye, but not every watery eye is a sore eye.
fields.creole: Eberysore yeye a watah yeye, but na ebery watah yeye a sore yeye

fields.english: Every thief knows his own trade.
fields.creole: Ebery tief man know he own trade

fields.english: Every time a chicken drinks water, it lifts its head up and says "Thank God".
fields.creole: Ebery time fowl drink watah, he hise he head a-tap an'say "Teng Gaad

fields.english: Every time it rains, the carrion crow swears he will build a house; when the sun comes out, he forgets.
fields.creole: Ebery time rain fall clarinclo swear he sa buil' house; when sun come out, he fo'get

fields.english: Every tub stands on its own bottom.
fields.creole: Ebery tub'tan' pon he own battam

fields.english: Every water is for drinking, but not every story is for telling.
fields.creole: Ebery watah fo' drink, but ebery 'tory no fo' tell

fields.english: Everywhere you turn, a close friend is there.
fields.creole: Ebery way you tu'n primo matty deh

fields.english: Not every wind is suitable for full sail.
fields.creole: Ebery win' na a-full sail

fields.english: The elephant knows that its backbone is big, that's why it tries to swallow a coconut.
fields.creole: Elephant sabby say be back-bone big da mek so he look fo' swalla coc'nut

fields.english: The elephant says, despite his size, he doesn't want trouble with man.
fields.creole: Elephant say wid all he big, he no wan' 'tory wid man

fields.english: An elephant's ears are big, but it doesn't hear its own story.
fields.creole: Elephant yase big, but he no a-yeddy he own 'tory

fields.english: An empty bag can't stand up.
fields.creole: Empty bag can't 'tan' up

fields.english: He can see his neighbor's faults, but can't see his own.
fields.creole: Eye can see he matty, but can't see hese'f

fields.english: Hard times make a man boil calalu (This means that difficult circumstances can force a person to make do with whatever they have, in this case, preparing a simple dish like calalu.)
fields.creole: Ha'd time mek man bile calalu

fields.english: Hard times make a poor man eat matty.
fields.creole: Ha'd time mek poo' man eat matty

fields.english: Hard times make a smoker smoke tobacco stick.
fields.creole: Ha'd time mek smoke man smoke tabacca 'tick

fields.english: It's hard to get butter out of a dog's throat.
fields.creole: Ha'd to get buttah out ob a daag t'roat

fields.english: Hair doesn't know what's in the head.
fields.creole: Hair na know wha' deh a-head

fields.english: A small problem creates a big issue that money can't solve.
fields.creole: Half-a-bitt mek trouble joe can't cure

fields.english: If your hand is in a tiger's mouth, you must pull it out very carefully.
fields.creole: Han' deh a-tigah mout', you mus' pull out safly safly

fields.english: A handful has company.
fields.creole: Han'-full hab company

fields.english: Give and take
fields.creole: Han' go, han' come

fields.english: Hands make rope, rope ties hands.
fields.creole: Han' mek rope, rope tie han'

fields.english: A girl with a handsome face is not necessarily the best kind of girl.
fields.creole: Han'some face gal na de besses kin' a gal

fields.english: When hands wash each other, both hands become clean.
fields.creole: Han' was' han' all too han' clean

fields.english: A harness doesn't fit a dog and a cat.
fields.creole: Harness no a-fit daag an' cat

fields.english: He carries his fortune on his back.
fields.creole: He a-carry he fortune on he back

fields.english: He keeps his book so well that even a cockroach can't get it.
fields.creole: He a-keep book so da cockroach se'f can't get am

fields.english: Heavy clouds, no rain
fields.creole: Heavy clould, no rain

fields.english: He went through the woods and picked up a crooked stick.
fields.creole: He bin t'rough the woods, an' he pick up a crooked 'tick

fields.english: He blows hot and cold with the same mouth.
fields.creole: He blow hot an' col' wid de same mout'

fields.english: He has the key to the street.
fields.creole: He gat de key a de street

fields.english: He already has a sheep's head.
fields.creole: He gat sheep head a-ready

fields.english: He is like a ship without a bottom.
fields.creole: He like a ship widout a battam

fields.english: His mouth is as sweet as a pot full of rice.
fields.creole: He mout' sweet like a rice-full pat

fields.english: He is not at the water container.
fields.creole: He na deh a-gooby

fields.english: Hang your basket where your hand can reach it.
fields.creole: Heng you' quake weh you' han' can meet am

fields.english: He picked my teeth to get to my gums.
fields.creole: He pick a-me teet' fo' get a-me gums

fields.english: The herring came to ask the pickle how it's doing.
fields.creole: Herrin' come fo' ask pickle how he situate

fields.english: His tongue doesn't have a bone, it's like a clock.
fields.creole: He tongue na gat leb na clock

fields.english: Secure the cow before you negotiate to sell the beef.
fields.creole: Hol' de cow befo' you bargain fo' sell de beef

fields.english: The cat got burnt by hot water, now it's scared even of cold water.
fields.creole: Hot watah bu'n cat, when he see col' watah he friken

fields.english: Houri told Patwa one day we will meet at the stop-off.
fields.creole: Houri tell patwa wan day awe sa meet a-'tap off

fields.english: Greetings and thanks break no bones
fields.creole: Howdee an' tenkee break no bones

fields.english: A hundred dollars is in a house, nobody hears; but when death occurs, there's too much crying.
fields.creole: Hundred dallah get in a house, nobody no yeddy; but dead get in, too much cry

fields.english: Hunger makes a man's mouth corner white.
fields.creole: Hungry belly mek man mout' ca'nah white

fields.english: A hungry man doesn't know that soup is sweet.
fields.creole: Hungry belly man na know soup na sweet

fields.english: Hunger tells a sweet mouth to "stand aside".
fields.creole: Hungry belly tell sweet mout' " 'Tan' wan side

fields.english: Hunger drove the Chinese man, he ate a snake.
fields.creole: Hungry bode (take hold of) Chinee, he nyam snake

fields.english: Hunger has no master.
fields.creole: Hungry gat no massa

fields.english: A hungry man looks for something to eat, even if it's just salt; a satisfied man finds fault.
fields.creole: Hungry man look fo' nyam salt ; man satisfy, he fin' fault

fields.english: Hunger makes a man thin.
fields.creole: Hungry mek man magah

fields.english: If you're not hungry, don't curse the thief.
fields.creole: Hungry no bode you, no cuss tief man

fields.english: Rushing leads to poor results.
fields.creole: Hurry hurry mek bad curry

fields.english: If an alligator comes out of the water's bottom and tells you, "The water mamma is blind," you must believe it.
fields.creole: If alligittah come out a-watah battam tell you say, "Watah mamma yeye blin'," you mus' belieb am

fields.english: If I tell you last year's story, you'll have tears in your eyes.
fields.creole: If a tell you las' yeah 'tory, watah run a-you yeye

fields.english: If a bad reputation could kill a rat, all rats would be dead.
fields.creole: If bad name could kill rat, all ratta go dead

fields.english: If a coal pot doesn't have a bottom, fire can't stand.
fields.creole: If coal pat na gat battam, fiah can't 'tan'

fields.english: If the chicken coop is full, a chicken can't make rat eggs hatch.
fields.creole: If fowl house full, fowl can't mek ratten eggs hatch

fields.english: If the greedy person waits, the soup will cool.
fields.creole: If greedy wait, hot sa cool

fields.english: If he had a spoon, he would drink soup.
fields.creole: If he bin hab spoon, he sa drink soup

fields.english: If he had spat him out, he couldn't resemble him more.
fields.creole: If he bin spit he out, he couldn't favah he mo'

fields.english: If a donkey could talk, it would say "Oh, poor Job!"
fields.creole: If jackass could a-talk he sa say "Aow, poo' Job!

fields.english: If a man is idle, he tempts the devil.
fields.creole: If man am idle, he temp' de debil

fields.english: If a man milks a cow, he must drink milk.
fields.creole: If man milk cow, he mus' drink milk

fields.english: If a man doesn't bend his back, he will hit his head on a post.
fields.creole: If man na ben' he back, he go jam he head a-post

fields.english: If a man sits up high and he falls, he will break his neck.
fields.creole: If man si' down high an' he fall, he go bruck he neck

fields.english: If I had known, it's always behind the door.
fields.creole: If me bin know always deh behin' de doo

fields.english: If I had known it would have bad consequences
fields.creole: If me bin know is a bad after-blow

fields.english: If I had known, I would have lost my child for its mother.
fields.creole: If me bin know, me loss picknie fo' mamma

fields.english: If my man doesn't beat me, he doesn't love me.
fields.creole: If me man no beat me, he no lobe me

fields.english: If a child doesn't hear "Stop," they won't hear "Be careful."
fields.creole: If picknie no heah "Done," he no heah "Tek ca'

fields.english: If a snake bites you and you see a lizard, you must run.
fields.creole: If snake bite you an' you see lizar', you mus' run

fields.english: If the sun hasn't set, a man hasn't finished crying.
fields.creole: If sun no done, man no done cry

fields.english: If a stranger heard what his walking stick said, he would never go to a strange man's house.
fields.creole: If 'tranjah man bin heah wha' he walkin'-'tick say, he nebba go a-'trange man house

fields.english: If trousers say the master is a thief, you can't doubt it.
fields.creole: If trouses say massa tief, you can't paca (doubt.)

fields.english: If the eye doesn't see, the mouth can't talk.
fields.creole: If yeye no see, mout' can't talk

fields.english: If you blow fire with your mouth, ashes will go in your eyes.
fields.creole: If you blow fiah wid you mout', ashes sa go a-you yeye

fields.english: If you can't get turkey, you must be satisfied with John Crow (a vulture or undesirable option).
fields.creole: If you can't get tu'key, you mus' satisfy wid John Crow

fields.english: If you're greedy for your friend's stew, you'll end up buying bread for the cat with the smell.
fields.creole: If you craben fo' you matty chue (stew), you sa buy bread fo' cat wid de scent

fields.english: If you insult the John Crow by calling it "bald head," the guinea hen gets angry.
fields.creole: If you cuss John Crow "Peel head," guinea hen bex

fields.english: If you eat labba (a small wild animal) and drink creek water, you won't be able to leave the country.
fields.creole: If you eat labba an' drink creek watah, you no able fo lef' de country

fields.english: If your finger gets sore, don't cut it off and throw it away.
fields.creole: If you fingah get sore, na cut am t'row 'way

fields.english: If you follow the spring tide, you will be left at the dam.
fields.creole: If you fallow spring tide, you sa lef' a-dam

fields.english: If you go to a new place, don't curse where you came from.
fields.creole: If you go a-new place, na cuss weh you come out

fields.english: If you're handsome, there's trouble; if you're ugly, there's trouble.
fields.creole: If you han'some da trouble, if you hugly da trouble

fields.english: If you rush, your soup will be salty.
fields.creole: If you hurry, you' soup salt

fields.english: If you like the dog, you must like its tail.
fields.creole: If you like dang, you mus' like 'e tail

fields.english: If you don't blow your own trumpet, your neighbor won't blow it for you.
fields.creole: If you no blow you' own trumpet, you' matty no go blow am fo' you

fields.english: If you don't come back before the spit dries, I'll know you've been playing.
fields.creole: If you no come back befo' spit dry, me know you bin a-play

fields.english: If you don't know the story, ask Jim Crow what happened to John Crow at the high dam pasture.
fields.creole: If you no know 'tory, ask Jim Crow wha' happen John Crow a-high dam pastah

fields.english: If you don't live in a house, you don't know where it leaks.
fields.creole: If you no libe a-house, you no know weh he a-leak

fields.english: If you don't interfere with the witch doctor, the witch doctor will never finish you for money.
fields.creole: If you no meddle wid obeahman, obeahman nebba dun you fo' money

fields.english: If your right eye twitches, you will meet something good, if your left eye twitches, you will encounter something bad.
fields.creole: If you' right eye dance you sa meet good, if you' lef' eye dance you sa meet bad

fields.english: If you think I'm a fool, put your hand to my mouth.
fields.creole: If you t'ink me a fool, put you' han' a-me mout'

fields.english: If you want a white person to be pleased (lick his lips), give him plantain water in a calabash.
fields.creole: If you wan' Bacra lickrish (lick his lips) gie am plantain watah a-calabash

fields.english: If you want to eat toad, eat it with egg.
fields.creole: If you wan' fo' eat crapaud, eat am wid egg

fields.english: If you want to know the story, take a walk abroad.
fields.creole: If you wan' no 'tory, tek you' walk abroad

fields.english: If you want to see a monkey cry, stick pepper in its eye.
fields.creole: If you wan' see monkey cry, 'tick peppah in he eye

fields.english: If there's no wick, the lamp can't burn.
fields.creole: If wick na deh, lamp can't bu'n

fields.english: If the wind doesn't blow, the leaf doesn't shake.
fields.creole: If win' no blow, leaf no shake

fields.english: If the wind doesn't blow, you won't see the chicken's backside.
fields.creole: If win no blow, you no see fowl back

fields.english: If you act hastily, you will regret it.
fields.creole: If you yeye jump, you a-go cry

fields.english: I am a saucepan without a cover.
fields.creole: I is saucepan widout a cubbah

fields.english: It's a calabash whip for hitting the witch doctor with.
fields.creole: Is calabash whip fo' lick obeahman wid

fields.english: It's the answer that causes the argument.
fields.creole: Is de ansah does bring de row

fields.english: The luck of a lousy cat is astonishing.
fields.creole: Is de luck ob a lousy cat does 'tonish

fields.english: You shouldn't be afraid of a dog that's not barking at you.
fields.creole: Is no daag wah a-bark you mus' friken

fields.english: It's what comes out of your mouth that causes trouble, not what's in your belly.
fields.creole: Is wha' come out a-you' mout dá mek trouble, na wha' deh a-you belly

fields.english: There's no situation so bad that it can't improve.
fields.creole: It is a bad tide which cannot turn

fields.english: It takes a very smart man to catch a hare.
fields.creole: It tek very smart man fo ketch accouri

fields.english: The donkey is in the bush, but the governor is in the house.
fields.creole: Jackass a-bush, but gubnah a-house

fields.english: The donkey drinks rum, but the hog gets drunk.
fields.creole: Jackass drink rum, haag get drunk

fields.english: If a bull is loose in the pasture, a person is not obliged to walk near it.
fields.creole: Bull loose a-pasture, man no bound fo' walk close am

fields.english: The bull is old, he smeared his tail.
fields.creole: Bull ol,' he smear he tail

fields.english: The bush is burning behind the tiger, and the tiger doesn't smell the smoke.
fields.creole: Bush bu'n behin' tigah, an' tigah no smell smoke

fields.english: The bush has ears
fields.creole: Bush gat yase

fields.english: Buy your food, eat according to your money.
fields.creole: Buy you' nyam, nyam accordin' to you money

fields.english: Ugly chickens eat good corn.
fields.creole: Caba ca-ba fowl nyam good co'n

fields.english: A calabash can float in a trench, but it can't float in a river.
fields.creole: Calabash a-float a-trench, but can't float a-ribah,

fields.english: A calabash is a poor man's finger basin.
fields.creole: Calabash a poo-man fingah basin

fields.english: The outside of a calabash is green, but its inside is white.
fields.creole: Calabash outside green, but he belly white

fields.english: A boa constrictor looks good if there are ants before it lies down.
fields.creole: Camoodi does look good if ants deh befo' he lie down

fields.english: You can't destroy Penitence to make Ruimveldt good.
fields.creole: Can't bruck Penitent fo' mek Rumfelt good

fields.english: "Can't help" is not done on purpose.
fields.creole: Can't help" no do fo' purpose

fields.english: Can't fatten a cow for another butcher
fields.creole: Can't fatten cow fo' nadda butcher

fields.english: Can't stop the river from running.
fields.creole: Can't tap de ribah from runnin'

fields.english: You can't use your bare eyes to roast my corn.
fields.creole: Can't tek you dry eye fo' roas' me co'n

fields.english: The captain of a man-of-war became a cook on a Guinea ship.
fields.creole: Cap'n a-man-o-war tu'n cook a-Guinea ship

fields.english: Captain Trust has died, bad pay killed him.
fields.creole: Cap'n Trus' gone dead, bad pay a-kill am

fields.english: Captain Trust has gone home.
fields.creole: Cap'n Trus' gone home

fields.english: The carrion crow eats the cow, but the cow can't eat the carrion crow.
fields.creole: Carrin crow a-nyam cow, cow can't nyam carrin crow

fields.english: The carrion crow says, "The mercy of the Lord is not on a tree."
fields.creole: Carrin crow say, "De mercy ob de Laad no deh 'pon tree

fields.english: The carrion crow says, "There is one God above, he never eats grass."
fields.creole: Carrin crow say, "Wan Gaad deh a-tap, he nebbah nyam grass

fields.english: Carrow follows the carrion crow, he sleeps by the fire side.
fields.creole: Carrow falla carrincrow, he sleep a-fiah side

fields.english: Cassava and okra can't make a good soup.
fields.creole: Cassada an' ochro can't mek good soup

fields.english: If the cassava is not ripe, do not scratch its bottom.
fields.creole: Cassada no ripe, no 'cratch he battam

fields.english: The cat is chasing the rat, but it's stealing its master's pork.
fields.creole: Cat a-dribe rat, but he tief he massa po'k

fields.english: When a cat plays with a bone, the dog wants it.
fields.creole: Cat a-play wid bone, daag want am

fields.english: A cat's paw is soft, but it can scratch indeed.
fields.creole: Cat foot saf', but he 'cratch fo' true

fields.english: When the cat's away, the rat takes over.
fields.creole: Cat no deh, ratta tek over

fields.english: "Deceitful lives a handful do."
fields.creole: 'Ceitful lib a-han'-fu11 doo'

fields.english: Chance can knock down even the devil himself.
fields.creole: Chance blow knack down de debil se'f

fields.english: Exchange for exchange
fields.creole: Changee fo' changee

fields.english: Talk to her, boy, you can win her over.
fields.creole: Chat am, boy, you sa win am

fields.english: Cheap things make everyone buy.
fields.creole: Cheap t'ing mek all man buy

fields.english: The chicken-hawk says, if he can't get the mother, he'll take the child.
fields.creole: Chicken-hawk say, he can't get mamma, he tek picknie

fields.english: The chicken-hawk says, he lives by his skill; the carrion-crow, by the grace of God.
fields.creole: Chicken-hawk say, he lib by he skill; carrin-crow, by de grace ob God

fields.english: A chicken hawk never builds its nest with a ground dove.
fields.creole: Chicken hawk nebba buil' he nes' wid ground dove

fields.english: The foolish hawk bought his rum, the goat drank it, but the sheep got drunk.
fields.creole: Chupit haag buy he rum, goat drink am, but sheep get drunk

fields.english: The foolish man gave away his spoon and ate with his hand.
fields.creole: Chupit man gie 'way he 'poon, an' eat wid 'e han.'

fields.english: A foolish man will close his neighbor's sluice, and leave his own open.
fields.creole: Chupit man go shut he matty kokah, an' lef' he own open

fields.english: A foolish man lets the water carry away his food twice.
fields.creole: Chupit man mek watah car''way he lap two time

fields.english: The foolish man melts lead in a sardine can.
fields.creole: Chupit man melt lead a-sardine pat

fields.english: A foolish man raced against a horse.
fields.creole: Chupit man run race wid hass

fields.english: A foolish man works and saves his money; when he dies, a wise man spends it.
fields.creole: Chupit man wo'k, put he money; when he dead, sense man spen' am

fields.english: A foolish man wrote it, a wise man can't read it.
fields.creole: Chupit man write am, sense man can't read am

fields.english: The carrion crow governor told the dog to show himself.
fields.creole: Claninclo a-gubnah tell daag show hese'f

fields.english: Cloth is easy to get dirty, but hard to wash.
fields.creole: Clat' easy fo' dutty, but haad fo' was'

fields.english: The rooster crows at the door, it's a sign that a stranger is coming.
fields.creole: Cock crow a-doo' mout', a sign 'tranger a-come

fields.english: The rooster scrambles, the hen scrambles, the children scramble, they can't sleep hungry.
fields.creole: Cock grabble, hen grabble, picknie grabble, dem can't sleep hungry

fields.english: The cockroach is always so drunk, it never walks into the chicken's house.
fields.creole: Cockroach ebba so drunk, he no walk a-fowl house

fields.english: The cockroach said it had feet to run, but the centipede caught it.
fields.creole: Cockroach say he gat foot fo' run, but sentapee catch am

fields.english: A coconut tree branch never fights a strong wind.
fields.creole: Coc'nut tree branch nebba fight high win'

fields.english: "Come, come," is a sweet, fish.
fields.creole: Come, come," is a sweet, fish

fields.english: There's more corn flour than water.
fields.creole: Co'n flour mo' dan watah

fields.english: The Congo eel is still considered a fish.
fields.creole: Congo eel still is a fish

fields.english: Congo mulatto, who is going to marry you?
fields.creole: Congo mulatto, who sa marry you?

fields.english: Congo sir lives a handful door.
fields.creole: Congo sah lib a-han'-full doo

fields.english: Consequences are why the crab has no head.
fields.creole: Consequential mek crab hab no head

fields.english: A contented man eats pepper and salt for breakfast.
fields.creole: Contented man eat peppah an' sal' fo' breakfast

fields.english: If the thick porridge doesn't choke you, don't drink the okra soup.
fields.creole: Coo-coo no choke you no drink ochro soup

fields.english: The laborer has a clean dam for washing, he sits down and says he is truly grieving.
fields.creole: Coolie gat clean dam fo' dutty, he si' down say he a-prap sorrow

fields.english: The Indian man wears a loincloth, it's no wonder, it's the fashion in his country.
fields.creole: Coolie wear baba, na wandah, da he country fashion

fields.english: The Cottee-cotte soup has all its steam at the bottom.
fields.creole: Cottee-cotte-soup hab all he 'team a-battam

fields.english: Country destroys country
fields.creole: Country kill country

fields.english: The country has changed, but my heart hasn't changed.
fields.creole: Country tu'n, but me haat no tu'n

fields.english: A cowardly man keeps all his bones intact.
fields.creole: Coward man keep whole bone

fields.english: When the cow dies, it leaves its skin as a story.
fields.creole: Cow dead, he lef' 'tory gie he 'kin

fields.english: When the cow dies, its owner cries; the carrion crow laughs.
fields.creole: Cow dead, he massa cry; carrin crow laugh

fields.english: The cow is in the pasture, it doesn't remember the butcher and the dog until it sees them.
fields.creole: Cow deh a-pastah, he no membah butchah an' daag teh he see am

fields.english: The cow never says "Goodbye" to the pasture.
fields.creole: Cow nebbah tell pastah "Goo' bye

fields.english: The cow doesn't eat pepper, but it fertilizes it.
fields.creole: Cow no eat peppah, but he down a-manure am

fields.english: If a cow doesn't have a tail, God Almighty will swat the flies.
fields.creole: Cow no hab tail, Gaad A'mighty brush fly

fields.english: The cow doesn't realize its loss until the fly season.
fields.creole: Cow no know he loss 'e tail teh cow-fly season

fields.english: The cow says it's dirty because of the dam, but it's actually dirty because of its own tail.
fields.creole: Cow say he dutty 'pon dam, but he dutty he own tail

fields.english: A cow's tail never surpasses its head.
fields.creole: Cow tail nebba pass he head

fields.english: A greedy dog loses both the corn and its husk.
fields.creole: Craben daag a-loss co'n an' husk

fields.english: The crab knows its hole, but the toad doesn't know its hole.
fields.creole: Crab know he 'ole, but crapaud na know he 'ole

fields.english: If a crab doesn't move, it doesn't get fat; if it moves too much, it gets hit.
fields.creole: Crab no walk he no get fat; he walk too much, he get a-pat

fields.english: Scrape your own calabash, before you scrape your neighbor's own.
fields.creole: 'Crape you own calabash, befo' you 'crape you matty own

fields.english: The frog didn't know the water was hot until it fell on its back.
fields.creole: Crapaud no bin sabby too watah teh hot watah fall a-he back

fields.english: A crazy man knows who the governor is.
fields.creole: Crazy man know gubnah

fields.english: The crow is always ready for a funeral, that's why it wears its burial suit.
fields.creole: Crow always ready fo' funeral mek he wear he berrin' suit

fields.english: A child who cries all the time will never get their way.
fields.creole: Cry-cry picknie nehba hab right

fields.english: Cuffy! Come see fish in the muddy water.
fields.creole: Cuffy! come see fish a-muddy watah

fields.english: Arguments never left a mark on my skin.
fields.creole: Cuss-cuss nebba bore hole a-me 'kin

fields.english: Cut off a cow's horn, you don't cut its heart.
fields.creole: Cut cow handle, you no cut he haat

fields.english: Envy doesn't kill a dog.
fields.creole: Cut yeye na a-kill daag

fields.english: The dog bites his friend, but he doesn't bite himself.
fields.creole: Daag a-bite he matty, but he no a-bite hese'f

fields.english: The dog is biting its tail, but it's not barking at itself.
fields.creole: Daag a-bite he tail, but he na a-bark 'pon hese'f

fields.english: The dog bites the master, but the master doesn't bite the dog.
fields.creole: Daag a-bite massa, but massa na a-bite daag

fields.english: The dog always lies down where the bone is being stirred.
fields.creole: Daag always lie down da place bone a-'tir

fields.english: Dog and cat can't eat from the same plate.
fields.creole: Dang an' cat can't eat a-wan plate

fields.english: The dog is running for its character, the hog is running for its life.
fields.creole: Daag a-run fo' he charatah, haag a-run fo' he life

fields.english: When the dog is present, it's "Mr. Dog"; when the dog is not present, it's just "Dog".
fields.creole: Daag deh, "Mr. Daag"; daag no deh, no mo' "Daag

fields.english: The dog drinks water noisily for itself, but not for us.
fields.creole: Daag drink watah chakoo chakoo fi you a-fi you, but fi awe no fi you

fields.english: "A dog with a broken foot knows the mouth of its master's door."
fields.creole: Daag foot-bruck, he know he massa doo' mout.'

fields.english: The dog has money to buy butter to roast on the fire.
fields.creole: Daag gat money buy buttah roas' a-fiah

fields.english: If a dog had money, he would buy cheese.
fields.creole: Daag gat money, he buy cheese

fields.english: A dog has four feet, but can't walk four roads at once.
fields.creole: Daag hab four foot, but can't walk four road wan time

fields.english: If a dog has too many masters, it will starve.
fields.creole: Daag hab too much massa him 'tarve

fields.english: The dog lapped water saying "What's yours is yours."
fields.creole: Daag lap watah say " Fo' you da fo' you

fields.english: What's happening, look out quickly before it passes.
fields.creole: Wha' a-pass, look out quick befo' he pass

fields.english: What comes from the devil's back goes under his belly.
fields.creole: Wha' come from de debil back go undah he belly

fields.english: What comes out of your stomach won't go into mine.
fields.creole: Wha' come out a-you belly no a-go in a-me own

fields.english: What comes out must go in.
fields.creole: Wha' come out sa go in

fields.english: What is the house in front of you, what is the bush for us.
fields.creole: Wha' da-house a-fo' you, wha' da-bush a-f' awe

fields.english: What's on the ground is for the dog, but not all dogs will pick it up.
fields.creole: Wha' deh a-groun' fo' daag, but no all daag a-pick am

fields.english: What's in the stick's head, is in the snake's head.
fields.creole: Wah' deh a stick head, deh a-snake head

fields.english: What's in your stomach doesn't need to come out of your mouth.
fields.creole: Wha' deh a-you belly na mek am pass t'rough you' mout'

fields.english: What's in the old goat must be in the kid.
fields.creole: Wha' deh in de ol' goat mus' be in de picknie

fields.english: What falls in the fire, you will find it in the ashes.
fields.creole: Wha' fall a-fiah you sa fin' am a-ashes

fields.english: What falls from the head goes to the shoulder.
fields.creole: Wha' fall from head go a-shouldah

fields.english: What was the fly doing before the cow got a sore eye?
fields.creole: Wha' fly bin a-do befo' cow get sore yeye?

fields.english: What can a fly do with a turtle's back?
fields.creole: Wha' fly can do wid tu'tle' back?

fields.english: What happens to the black fowl will happen to the white fowl.
fields.creole: Wha' happen to black fowl sa happen to white fowl

fields.english: What hurts the eye makes the nose run water.
fields.creole: Wha' hu't yeye mek nose run watah

fields.english: What was the Mahaica man doing before Munro's horse died of glanders?
fields.creole: Wha' Mahaica niggah bin a-do befo' Munro glandas haas dead?

fields.english: What motion quicksilver has at the bottom, it doesn't have at the top.
fields.creole: Wha' motion quicksilver got a-battam, he na gat a-sluice

fields.english: What's not good for breakfast is not good for dinner.
fields.creole: Wha' no good fo' breakfas' no good fo' dinnah

fields.english: What has passed, let it go; what is to come, sit down and wait for it.
fields.creole: Wha' pass chase am let 'e go, wha' a-come si down wait am

fields.english: What sense is in a snake's head, the same is in a stick's head.
fields.creole: Wha' sense deb a-snake head, de same deh a-bostick-head

fields.english: What does the term "tocle" have to do with a cow-fly?
fields.creole: Wha' some'ting tocle sa do wid cow-fly?

fields.english: What the eye doesn't see, the heart doesn't burn for.
fields.creole: Wha' yeye no see haat no bu'n

fields.english: What the ears don't hear, the heart doesn't burn over.
fields.creole: Wha' ears no heah haat no bu'n

fields.english: What your eyes don't see, your mouth doesn't water for.
fields.creole: Wha' you' eye no see you mout' no run watah

fields.english: What you gain in one area, you lose in another.
fields.creole: Wha' you gain in jigging you lose in shuffling

fields.english: What you put in the pickle never spoils.
fields.creole: Wha' you put in de pickle nebbah 'pile

fields.english: What's too heavy for your hand, roll it on the ground.
fields.creole: Wha' too heaby fo' you han' roll am a-groun'

fields.english: What you lost in the saucepan, you must find in the bottom of the coal pot.
fields.creole: Wha' you loss a-saucepan you mus' fin' a-bottom coal pot

fields.english: When an aboriginal Indian wants to harm you, he says "Fair play, no pilfering".
fields.creole: When Buck wan' a-damage you he say "Fair play no pra pra

fields.english: When a building catches fire, the master begs the laborer for help.
fields.creole: When buil'in' a-ketch fiah massa beg labrah

fields.english: When two bulls meet, they call each other "Brother".
fields.creole: When bull an' bull meet dey call matty "Bro

fields.english: When two bulls are in conversation, the steer has no business there.
fields.creole: When bull an' bull a-chat, capoon na gat business deh

fields.english: When cassava and okra meet in the pot, the pot must burn.
fields.creole: When cassada an' ochro meet a-pat, pat mus' bu'n

fields.english: When the cat's belly is full, it says "The rat stinks".
fields.creole: When cat belly full, he say "Ratta 'tink

fields.english: When a cat can't get milk, it remembers there are birds in the bush.
fields.creole: When cat na get milk, he 'membah bi'd a-bush

fields.english: When the carrion crow gets an itch in its eye, it thinks it's a governor.
fields.creole: When claninclo get yeye-tickle he t'ink hese'f gubnah

fields.english: When the carrion crow has eaten its fill, it flaps its wings at its neighbor.
fields.creole: When claninclo nyam belly-full, he shake 'e wing 'pon 'e matty

fields.english: When a chigger is in your foot, it's as tough as being pricked with a cattan.
fields.creole: When chiggah foot a rattan 'tuff am wid cattan

fields.english: When a coconut falls from the tree, it can't be reattached.
fields.creole: When coc'nut fall from tree he can't fasten back

fields.english: When a cockroach hosts a dance, he doesn't invite the chicken.
fields.creole: When cockroach gie dance, he no hax fowl

fields.english: When a poor man gets money, he shakes the governor's hand.
fields.creole: When cocoby man get money, 'e shake gubnah han'

fields.english: When a tough man meets another tough man, he says "There's no time."
fields.creole: When cuffman meet cuffman he say "Time no deh

fields.english: When a dog gets hit, it tucks its tail under its belly and runs away, yelping for sure, but watch out when it comes back.
fields.creole: When daag get lick he put 'e tail under he belly an' run an' halla fo' true, but look sharp when he come back

fields.english: When pork is delicious, a person keeps it in their mouth for a long time.
fields.creole: When flesin po'k sweet, man a-keep am lang a-he mout'

fields.english: When one bird meets another in bird country, one tells the other "Just like that!"
fields.creole: When fowl an' fowl meet a-fowl country, tara tell tara "So by
