fields.english: When the rooster gets drunk, he forgets that the black-handled knife is in the kitchen.
fields.creole: When fowl-cock get grog, he fo'get say "black 'andle knife deh a-kitchen

fields.english: When chickens have teeth and dogs eat razors.
fields.creole: When fowl get teet' an' daag nyam razah

fields.english: When the ibis sees fish, it forgets that there's a gun.
fields.creole: When galin see fish, he fo'get say "Gun deh

fields.english: When a goat wants to roll, it rolls without the wind blowing it.
fields.creole: When goat down wan' roll he roll widout win' blow am

fields.english: When there's no horse, a donkey takes first place.
fields.creole: When haas na deh, jackass mek fus' place

fields.english: When he is calling God's name, that's when he is lying.
fields.creole: When he a-call Gad name, á de time he lie

fields.english: When he is here, he is here, when he is not here, he is not here.
fields.creole: When he deh he deh, when he na deh he na deh

fields.english: When the herring is fat and cooking, not everyone gets to smell it.
fields.creole: When herrin' fat a-bu'n, na all man a-smell am

fields.english: When a coolie (a person of Indian descent) is hungry, he is happy to eat pork.
fields.creole: When hungry ketch coolie, he glad fo' eat po'k

fields.english: When a donkey kicks a man, the man shouldn't bother to kick it back.
fields.creole: When jackass kick man, man mus'n't baddah kick am back

fields.english: When a little boy puts on a big man's trousers, he must accept what he gets.
fields.creole: When li'l boy put on big man trouses, wha' he get he mus' take

fields.english: When a small dog has a big liver, it will die before its time.
fields.creole: When li'l daag gat big libah, he go dead befo' 'e time

fields.english: When a little child wants to run, give him a long rope.
fields.creole: When li'l niggah wan' run, gie am lang rope

fields.english: When a man is going to eat at a woman's house, he must let the woman eat first.
fields.creole: When man a-go eat a-wan ooman 'ouse, he mus' leh a ooman eat fus'

fields.english: When a man is about to jump a fence, he must look carefully before he jumps.
fields.creole: When man a-go jump fence, he must look good befo' he jump

fields.english: When a man is writing, do not touch his pen.
fields.creole: When man a-write, no touch he pen

fields.english: When a man buys butter, his friend dips his finger deep.
fields.creole: When man buy buttah, he matty chook he fingah deep

fields.english: When a man is living well, he calls God "Congah".
fields.creole: When man get good libin' he call God "Congah

fields.english: When a man makes himself sugar, his friends will surely suck it.
fields.creole: When man mek hese'f sugah, 'e matty suck am fo' true

fields.english: When a man doesn't have a match, he uses a fire-stick to light the lamp.
fields.creole: When man na gat match he tek fiah-'tick fo' light lamp

fields.english: When a man sucks cane, he throws its peel on the ground.
fields.creole: When man suck cane, 'e mash 'e pilin' a-groun.'

fields.english: When a man wants to beat a dog, he finds a stick quickly.
fields.creole: When man wan' fo' beat daag, he 'fin' 'tick quick

fields.english: When my foot itches me, it's a sign that I'm going to walk.
fields.creole: When me foot itch me, a sign me go walk

fields.english: When my left hand itches, money is coming.
fields.creole: When me lef' han' 'cratch me, money a-come

fields.english: When my eyes are dancing, it's a sign I'm going to cry.
fields.creole: When me yeye a-dance, a sign me go cry

fields.english: When one tooth hurts you, all the rest are upset.
fields.creole: When one toot' hu't you, all de res' bex

fields.english: When the patwa (a type of fish) sees bait, it forgets that there's a hook at the bottom.
fields.creole: When patwa see bait, 'e fo'get say "'Ook de a-battam

fields.english: When a puppy gets plenty of milk, it turns up its nose at salt soup.
fields.creole: When puppy get plenty milk, he mek up he face 'pon sal' soup

fields.english: When it's drizzling, the devil and his wife are fighting for a ham bone.
fields.creole: When rain a-drizzle, debil an' he wife a-fight fo' ham bone

fields.english: When it's raining and the sun is shining, the devil is beating his wife.
fields.creole: When rain fall an' sun shining, debil licking he wife

fields.english: When a rat sees a cat, it never laughs.
fields.creole: When rat see cat, 'e nebbah laugh

fields.english: When the saucepan loses its cover, everyone peeps inside.
fields.creole: When saucepan loss he cobah, all man a-peep inside

fields.english: When a wound can't heal, one must sit down and bear it.
fields.creole: When sore can't get bettah, man gat fo' si' down bear am

fields.english: When the tiger gets old, the dog barks at it.
fields.creole: When ti'gah get ol', daag ba'k aftah am

fields.english: When the tiger is not there, the monkey gives the ball.
fields.creole: When tigal na deh, monkey gie ball

fields.english: When the tiger is sick, the deer lends him money.
fields.creole: When tigah sick, deer dun am fo' money

fields.english: When trouble comes, it doesn't blow its shell.
fields.creole: When trouble come, he no blow 'e shell

fields.english: When a white person gets into trouble, even a monkey's trousers will fit him.
fields.creole: When trouble ketch Bacra, monkey breeches fit am

fields.english: When trouble catches a man, he stands up and staggers; When trouble catches a woman, she sits down and considers.
fields.creole: When trouble ketch man, he 'tan' up an' 'taggah; When trouble ketch ooman, him si-down an' considah

fields.english: When two big bottles are on the table, the little one has no business there.
fields.creole: When two big bottle deh a-table, little wan no bu'iness

fields.english: When the barrel doesn't have a hoop, it must break down.
fields.creole: When tub na got hoople, he mus' bruck down

fields.english: When two dogs are fighting, the cat stands to one side.
fields.creole: When two daag get quarrel, Tom cat 'tan wan side

fields.english: When your brother is in trouble, don't laugh at him.
fields.creole: When you bruddah soak, don' laugh he

fields.english: When you're dead, you don't know, and when you know, you're already dead.
fields.creole: When you' dead you no sabby, an' when you sabby, you dead done

fields.english: When you get a donkey to ride, ride it for real.
fields.creole: When you get jackass fo' ride, ride am fo' true

fields.english: When you go into the bush, don't take the same road to come back.
fields.creole: When you go a-bush, no walk same road come back

fields.english: When you go to the countryside where they dance with one foot, you should also dance with one foot.
fields.creole: When you go a-country weh dem a-dance wid one foot, dance wid one foot too

fields.english: When you visit a friend's house, leave your appetite behind.
fields.creole: When you go a-frien' house, lef' you' 'tomach behin'

fields.english: When you have money, doors open; when you don't have, they shut.
fields.creole: When you gat money, doo' open; when you no gat, he shut

fields.english: When you have the devil to deal with, feed him with a long spoon.
fields.creole: When you hab de debil fo' deal wid, feed am wid long 'poon

fields.english: When your hand is yellow, dogs will make it so.
fields.creole: When you' han' yalla, daag mek so

fields.english: When you kill a bush cow, be careful how you carry it to the canoe.
fields.creole: When you kill comma, min' how you carry am a-canoe

fields.english: When you leave a wake, don't say "Good night".
fields.creole: When you lef' wake house, no say "Goo' night

fields.english: When you step on a dog, put on your shoes.
fields.creole: When you mash daag, put on you' shoes

fields.english: When your own louse bites you, it really bites you.
fields.creole: When you own louse bite you, he bite you fo' true

fields.english: Someone who cries inside the house, and someone who cries outside the door, it's the same thing.
fields.creole: A body wah cry a-house, an'a body wah cry a-doo', a same t'ing

fields.english: A person who they don't want to roast, should not sit near the fire.
fields.creole: A body wah dem no wan' fo' roas', no fo' si' down carnah fiah

fields.english: The agouti knows its teeth are strong; that's why it eats palm nuts.
fields.creole: Accouri know he teet' 'trang; da mek he eat banga

fields.english: The colony hare uses the alligator's teeth to make sugar cake.
fields.creole: Accouri tek cayman teet' he mek sugah cake

fields.english: I came to milk the cow, not to count the cattle.
fields.creole: A come fo' milk cow, no fo' reckon cattle

fields.english: A cow that cries for water doesn't really need it.
fields.creole: A cow wah cry fo' watah na he a-want am

fields.english: A dog has the liberty to watch the governor.
fields.creole: A daag hab libaty fo' watch a-de gubnah

fields.english: A dog's mouth prevents it from climbing a tree.
fields.creole: A daag mout' mek he can't climb tree

fields.english: After night, morning comes.
fields.creole: After night ma'nin' come

fields.english: Gold is causing the white man to die with yellow fever today.
fields.creole: A gold mek Bacra a dead wid yalla febah t'day

fields.english: A good friend is better than money in the pocket.
fields.creole: A good frien' is bettah dan money in de pocket

fields.english: It's hard to pay for music when you can't hear the banjo play.
fields.creole: A hard t'ing fo' pay fo' music when you no heah banja play

fields.english: A horse, with a good heart, allows a man to ride it as he likes.
fields.creole: A hass, good heart mek man a-ride am as he like

fields.english: A hint to Beniba makes Quashiba take notice.
fields.creole: A hint to Beniba mek Quashiba tek notice

fields.english: A little is better than nothing.
fields.creole: A little is bettah dan not'in.'

fields.english: All birds can sing, but not all birds can talk.
fields.creole: All bi'd can sing, but a11 bi'd can't talk

fields.english: All carrion crows eat dead meat, but not all dogs eat it.
fields.creole: All carrin crow a-nyam dead meat, but all dag na a-nyam am

fields.english: All cassava have the same skin, but they don't all taste the same way.
fields.creole: All cassada got same 'kin, but all na tas'e same way

fields.english: All cows are crying, but not all cows are butting.
fields.creole: All cow a-cry, but na all cow a-butt

fields.english: All dogs can bark, but some are scared to bite.
fields.creole: All daag can bark, but some frighten fo' bite

fields.english: Everyone can talk, but not everyone can listen.
fields.creole: All fool can talk, but na all can heah

fields.english: "Not all high beds are safe."
fields.creole: All high bed no saf.'

fields.english: Alligator and cayman, they're all the same thing.
fields.creole: Alligittah an' cayman, a11 same t'ing

fields.english: The alligator doesn't nurse its young, but they survive.
fields.creole: Alligittah no a-gie he picknie suck, but dem lib

fields.english: The alligator eats the frog to fill its belly, and the duck for its sweet taste.
fields.creole: Alligittah nyam crapaud fo'belly full, an' duck fo' sweet mout'

fields.english: The alligator saw a bird and thought it was a fish.
fields.creole: Alligittah see fowl, he say a fish

fields.english: All kinds of pleasure must have a stop-off.
fields.creole: All kin' ob plesha mus' get wan 'taff-aff

fields.english: Everyone can talk, but not everyone can act.
fields.creole: All man can talk, but na all can do

fields.english: All pork looks like meat, but not all are in season.
fields.creole: All po'k favah matty, but na all a-season

fields.english: Not all that is sweet is good, and not all that is bitter is bad.
fields.creole: All sweet na sweet, all bittah na bittah

fields.english: A man who doesn't know his own needs is a fool.
fields.creole: A man no know he own want is a fool

fields.english: An unlucky bird often gets an unlucky trap.
fields.creole: Anlucky bi'd often get anlucky trap

fields.english: Ants know when hard times are coming, that's why they carry plenty of food to store in their house.
fields.creole: Ants know hard time a-come, da mek he does carry plenty food fo' put a-he house

fields.english: Where there is water, that's where the blue fly lives.
fields.creole: A place fish watah deh, a de blue fly lib

fields.english: A place where a rat scrapes, you can see it from a distance, but where it stands up, you can't see it.
fields.creole: A place weh rat 'crape you a-see am fo' slice, weh he 'tan' up you no a-see am

fields.english: A pound of worry doesn't pay a gill of debt.
fields.creole: A pound ob fretment no pay a gill of debtment

fields.english: The same place where a thorn pricks your foot is the same place you must remove it from.
fields.creole: A same place pimplah chook you' foot, a same place you must take am out

fields.english: A spider had sense when the monkey went to kill it, it shouted that a gunman was coming.
fields.creole: A sense nancy bin got when monkey go fo' kill, he halla gun man a-come

fields.english: Where the ashes are cold, that's where the dog lies down.
fields.creole: Ashes col', daag lie down deh

fields.english: As his skin stands, so stands his heart.
fields.creole: As he 'kin 'tan', so 'tan' he heart

fields.english: As long as there are school teachers, what you don't know today, you will know tomorrow.
fields.creole: As long as school missy an' school massa deh, wha' you no know t'day you sa know to-morrow

fields.english: A tiger's size and intelligence is what allows it to live in the bush today.
fields.creole: A tigah bigness an' sense mek he lib a-bush to-day

fields.english: When the sun is setting, the hen doesn't gather her chicks, each one must fend for itself.
fields.creole: A time sun a-down fowl no a-grabble fo' he chicken, ya grabble fo' hese'f

fields.english: Watch your mouth, and I'll know what's going on inside your house.
fields.creole: A watch a-you' doo' mout', an' me know how you' house inside 'tan'

fields.english: We live in the bush.
fields.creole: Awe lib a-bush

fields.english: We two can't turn in the same pot.
fields.creole: Awe two coo-coo can't tu'n in de same pat

fields.english: When a baby is born, its feet are small.
fields.creole: Baby born, he foot small

fields.english: The back can wait, but not the stomach.
fields.creole: Back can wait, but no belly

fields.english: The white man saw the side-line dam before he walked a mile-long dam.
fields.creole: Bacra bin see side-line dam befo' he walk a mi'l-walk dam

fields.english: The white man is just like a cow's dung, he is dry on top, but wet at the bottom.
fields.creole: Bacra jus' like cow-down, he tap dry, he battam wet

fields.english: The white man is not a boy, the black man is not a fool.
fields.creole: Bacra no boy, niggah no fool

fields.english: If the white man doesn't speak, the black man won't understand.
fields.creole: Bacra no talk, niggah no sabby

fields.english: The white man stands like a doctor bird, he found sweet flowers on more than one tree.
fields.creole: Bacra 'tan' like dactah-bi'd, he fin sweet flower 'pon mo' 'an wan tree

fields.english: A bad cow gives a bucketful of milk and then kicks it over.
fields.creole: Bad cow gie bucketful milk an' kick am down

fields.english: No witchcraft can overcome a wicked heart.
fields.creole: Bad heart no obeah

fields.english: A bad musician makes noise with his foot.
fields.creole: Bad musicianer mek row wid he foot

fields.english: A bad reputation doesn't kill a rat.
fields.creole: Bad name no a-kill rat

fields.english: Trouble never has an owner
fields.creole: Bad nebbah gat ownah

fields.english: If the bag isn't full, it can't stand up.
fields.creole: Bag no full, he can't 'tan' up

fields.english: The baker never says his bread is sour.
fields.creole: Bakah nebhah Say 'e bread sour

fields.english: A deal is made before the country is taken.
fields.creole: Bargain mek befo' country tek

fields.english: The boat knows it doesn't have a keel, that's why it can't take a lot of sail.
fields.creole: Bateau know he na gat keel, da mek he can't tek plenty sail

fields.english: Battle without water is blowing "whoo-whoo" in the wind.
fields.creole: Battle berout watah a-blow "whoo-whoo" a-win'

fields.english: The battle is over, the water has run out.
fields.creole: Battle bore, watah run out

fields.english: The bat trusts himself, that's why he hangs from the rafters above.
fields.creole: Bat trus' hese'f mek he heng a-raftah tap

fields.english: If beef had no bones, dogs would have no business there.
fields.creole: Beef no ha' bone, daag no ha' no bu'iness deh

fields.english: In front of you, they act as if they're so innocent that not even butter would melt in their mouth, but behind your back, they're as harmful as a fire stick.
fields.creole: Befo' face like a buttah can't melt, behind back fiah 'tick

fields.english: Before farther, behind farther
fields.creole: Befo' farra, behin' farra

fields.english: Before marriage it's "my dear," after marriage it's "you brute."
fields.creole: Befo' wedding is "my dear," after wedding is "you brute.''

fields.english: A beggar is looking for work, but he is praying not to get it.
fields.creole: Beggah a-look fo' wo'k, but he a-pray fo' no get am

fields.english: A beggar begging from another beggar will never become rich.
fields.creole: Beggah beg from beggah nebbah grow rich

fields.english: Beg a man to work, but don't beg him to eat.
fields.creole: Beg man fo wo'k, but na beg am fo' eat

fields.english: Behind the back has no ears.
fields.creole: Behin' back no hab ear

fields.english: A man with a full belly tells a hungry man, "stay strong, buddy."
fields.creole: Belly-full man tell hungry man, "keep heart buddy

fields.english: A full belly breaks the pot.
fields.creole: Belly-full bruck pat

fields.english: Remember, if you spy on me, I will watch you too.
fields.creole: Bembah rubembah you peep me, me sa watch you

fields.english: It's better to watch a box full of cockroaches than a girl.
fields.creole: Bettah fo' watch wan ban'box full cockroach dan wan gal

fields.english: It's better to paddle your own canoe than to wait for your friend to paddle it for you.
fields.creole: Bettah paddle you' own canoe dan wait fo' you matty paddle am fo' you

fields.english: If a bird is angry with a tree, where will it perch?
fields.creole: Bi'd bex wid tree, weh he go 'tan' up?

fields.english: A bird that flies too high must pass its nest.
fields.creole: Bi'd fly too high mus' pass he nes'

fields.english: Big houses have big stories.
fields.creole: Big house ha' big 'tory

fields.english: The big river is overflowing its banks.
fields.creole: Big libah a-buss he belly

fields.english: A grown man doesn't run for no reason.
fields.creole: Big man no a-run fo' not'in'

fields.english: A big story overwhelms a dog.
fields.creole: Big 'tory choke daag

fields.english: The arrogant attitude choked the deceitful person.
fields.creole: Big yeye choke nancy cat

fields.english: Being ambitious made the man choose hard labor.
fields.creole: Big yeye mek niggah pick shovel 'tick

fields.english: Bill bird trusted himself to swallow a tooroo seed.
fields.creole: Bill bi'd trus' hese'f mek he swalla tooroo seed

fields.english: A black man as a master is the worst kind of master.
fields.creole: Black man massa de wossis kin' ob massa

fields.english: If a black man steals, he steals a small amount; if a white man steals, he steals an entire estate.
fields.creole: Black man tief, he tief half-a-bitt; bacra tief, he tief whole estate

fields.english: In a blind-eye country, a one-eyed man is governor.
fields.creole: Blin' yeye country, one yeye man a-gubnah

fields.english: A blind man can't carry news.
fields.creole: Blin' yeye man can't carry news

fields.english: A blind man knows his door's mouth.
fields.creole: Blin' yeye man know he doo' mout.'

fields.english: A blind man doesn't need a mirror.
fields.creole: Blin' yeye man na wan' lookin' glass

fields.english: A blind man never leaves his walking stick.
fields.creole: Blin' yeye man nebbah lef' he walking 'tick

fields.english: A boy and a boss can't court in the same house.
fields.creole: Boy an' bass can't cou'tin' a-wan house

fields.english: A boastful story doesn't hold water.
fields.creole: Briggah 'tory no lock a-gooby

fields.english: A boastful tongue is empty inside.
fields.creole: Briggah tongue hab empty inside

fields.english: A broom is not absent from anyone's house.
fields.creole: Broom na absen' a-nobody house

fields.english: The aboriginal Indian has time, he makes a wicker basket.
fields.creole: Buck gat time, he mek pegall

fields.english: The aboriginal Indian is enjoying himself, the aboriginal Indian's town is burning.
fields.creole: Buck a-plesha, Buck town a-bu'n

fields.english: What's happening, look out quickly before it passes.
fields.creole: Wha' a-pass, look out quick befo' he pass

fields.english: What comes from the devil's back goes under his belly.
fields.creole: Wha' come from de debil back go undah he belly

fields.english: What comes out of your stomach won't go into mine.
fields.creole: Wha' come out a-you belly no a-go in a-me own

fields.english: What comes out must go in.
fields.creole: Wha' come out sa go in

fields.english: What is the house in front of you, what is the bush for us.
fields.creole: Wha' da-house a-fo' you, wha' da-bush a-f' awe

fields.english: What's on the ground is for the dog, but not all dogs will pick it up.
fields.creole: Wha' deh a-groun' fo' daag, but no all daag a-pick am

fields.english: What's in the stick's head, is in the snake's head.
fields.creole: Wah' deh a stick head, deh a-snake head

fields.english: What's in your stomach doesn't need to come out of your mouth.
fields.creole: Wha' deh a-you belly na mek am pass t'rough you' mout'

fields.english: What's in the old goat must be in the kid.
fields.creole: Wha' deh in de ol' goat mus' be in de picknie

fields.english: What falls in the fire, you will find it in the ashes.
fields.creole: Wha' fall a-fiah you sa fin' am a-ashes

fields.english: What falls from the head goes to the shoulder.
fields.creole: Wha' fall from head go a-shouldah

fields.english: What was the fly doing before the cow got a sore eye?
fields.creole: Wha' fly bin a-do befo' cow get sore yeye?

fields.english: What can a fly do with a turtle's back?
fields.creole: Wha' fly can do wid tu'tle' back?

fields.english: What happens to the black fowl will happen to the white fowl.
fields.creole: Wha' happen to black fowl sa happen to white fowl

fields.english: What hurts the eye makes the nose run water.
fields.creole: Wha' hu't yeye mek nose run watah

fields.english: What was the Mahaica man doing before Munro's horse died of glanders?
fields.creole: Wha' Mahaica niggah bin a-do befo' Munro glandas haas dead?

fields.english: What motion quicksilver has at the bottom, it doesn't have at the top.
fields.creole: Wha' motion quicksilver got a-battam, he na gat a-sluice

fields.english: What's not good for breakfast is not good for dinner.
fields.creole: Wha' no good fo' breakfas' no good fo' dinnah

fields.english: What has passed, let it go; what is to come, sit down and wait for it.
fields.creole: Wha' pass chase am let 'e go, wha' a-come si down wait am

fields.english: What sense is in a snake's head, the same is in a stick's head.
fields.creole: Wha' sense deb a-snake head, de same deh a-bostick-head

fields.english: What does the term "tocle" have to do with a cow-fly?
fields.creole: Wha' some'ting tocle sa do wid cow-fly?

fields.english: What the eye doesn't see, the heart doesn't burn for.
fields.creole: Wha' yeye no see haat no bu'n

fields.english: What the ears don't hear, the heart doesn't burn over.
fields.creole: Wha' ears no heah haat no bu'n

fields.english: What your eyes don't see, your mouth doesn't water for.
fields.creole: Wha' you' eye no see you mout' no run watah

fields.english: What you gain in one area, you lose in another.
fields.creole: Wha' you gain in jigging you lose in shuffling

fields.english: What you put in the pickle never spoils.
fields.creole: Wha' you put in de pickle nebbah 'pile

fields.english: What's too heavy for your hand, roll it on the ground.
fields.creole: Wha' too heaby fo' you han' roll am a-groun'

fields.english: What you lost in the saucepan, you must find in the bottom of the coal pot.
fields.creole: Wha' you loss a-saucepan you mus' fin' a-bottom coal pot

fields.english: When an aboriginal Indian wants to harm you, he says "Fair play, no pilfering".
fields.creole: When Buck wan' a-damage you he say "Fair play no pra pra

fields.english: When a building catches fire, the master begs the laborer for help.
fields.creole: When buil'in' a-ketch fiah massa beg labrah

fields.english: When two bulls meet, they call each other "Brother".
fields.creole: When bull an' bull meet dey call matty "Bro

fields.english: When two bulls are in conversation, the steer has no business there.
fields.creole: When bull an' bull a-chat, capoon na gat business deh

fields.english: When cassava and okra meet in the pot, the pot must burn.
fields.creole: When cassada an' ochro meet a-pat, pat mus' bu'n

fields.english: When the cat's belly is full, it says "The rat stinks".
fields.creole: When cat belly full, he say "Ratta 'tink

fields.english: When a cat can't get milk, it remembers there are birds in the bush.
fields.creole: When cat na get milk, he 'membah bi'd a-bush

fields.english: When the carrion crow gets an itch in its eye, it thinks it's a governor.
fields.creole: When claninclo get yeye-tickle he t'ink hese'f gubnah

fields.english: When the carrion crow has eaten its fill, it flaps its wings at its neighbor.
fields.creole: When claninclo nyam belly-full, he shake 'e wing 'pon 'e matty

fields.english: When a chigger is in your foot, it's as tough as being pricked with a cattan.
fields.creole: When chiggah foot a rattan 'tuff am wid cattan

fields.english: When a coconut falls from the tree, it can't be reattached.
fields.creole: When coc'nut fall from tree he can't fasten back

fields.english: When a cockroach hosts a dance, he doesn't invite the chicken.
fields.creole: When cockroach gie dance, he no hax fowl

fields.english: When a poor man gets money, he shakes the governor's hand.
fields.creole: When cocoby man get money, 'e shake gubnah han'

fields.english: When a tough man meets another tough man, he says "There's no time."
fields.creole: When cuffman meet cuffman he say "Time no deh

fields.english: When a dog gets hit, it tucks its tail under its belly and runs away, yelping for sure, but watch out when it comes back.
fields.creole: When daag get lick he put 'e tail under he belly an' run an' halla fo' true, but look sharp when he come back

fields.english: When pork is delicious, a person keeps it in their mouth for a long time.
fields.creole: When flesin po'k sweet, man a-keep am lang a-he mout'

fields.english: When one bird meets another in bird country, one tells the other "Just like that!"
fields.creole: When fowl an' fowl meet a-fowl country, tara tell tara "So by

fields.english: When the rooster gets drunk, he forgets that the black-handled knife is in the kitchen.
fields.creole: When fowl-cock get grog, he fo'get say "black 'andle knife deh a-kitchen

fields.english: When chickens have teeth and dogs eat razors.
fields.creole: When fowl get teet' an' daag nyam razah

fields.english: When the ibis sees fish, it forgets that there's a gun.
fields.creole: When galin see fish, he fo'get say "Gun deh

fields.english: When a goat wants to roll, it rolls without the wind blowing it.
fields.creole: When goat down wan' roll he roll widout win' blow am

fields.english: When there's no horse, a donkey takes first place.
fields.creole: When haas na deh, jackass mek fus' place

fields.english: When he is calling God's name, that's when he is lying.
fields.creole: When he a-call Gad name, á de time he lie

fields.english: When he is here, he is here, when he is not here, he is not here.
fields.creole: When he deh he deh, when he na deh he na deh

fields.english: When the herring is fat and cooking, not everyone gets to smell it.
fields.creole: When herrin' fat a-bu'n, na all man a-smell am

fields.english: When a coolie (a person of Indian descent) is hungry, he is happy to eat pork.
fields.creole: When hungry ketch coolie, he glad fo' eat po'k

fields.english: When a donkey kicks a man, the man shouldn't bother to kick it back.
fields.creole: When jackass kick man, man mus'n't baddah kick am back

fields.english: When a little boy puts on a big man's trousers, he must accept what he gets.
fields.creole: When li'l boy put on big man trouses, wha' he get he mus' take

fields.english: When a small dog has a big liver, it will die before its time.
fields.creole: When li'l daag gat big libah, he go dead befo' 'e time

fields.english: When a little child wants to run, give him a long rope.
fields.creole: When li'l niggah wan' run, gie am lang rope

fields.english: When a man is going to eat at a woman's house, he must let the woman eat first.
fields.creole: When man a-go eat a-wan ooman 'ouse, he mus' leh a ooman eat fus'

fields.english: When a man is about to jump a fence, he must look carefully before he jumps.
fields.creole: When man a-go jump fence, he must look good befo' he jump

fields.english: When a man is writing, do not touch his pen.
fields.creole: When man a-write, no touch he pen

fields.english: When a man buys butter, his friend dips his finger deep.
fields.creole: When man buy buttah, he matty chook he fingah deep

fields.english: When a man is living well, he calls God "Congah".
fields.creole: When man get good libin' he call God "Congah

fields.english: When a man makes himself sugar, his friends will surely suck it.
fields.creole: When man mek hese'f sugah, 'e matty suck am fo' true

fields.english: When a man doesn't have a match, he uses a fire-stick to light the lamp.
fields.creole: When man na gat match he tek fiah-'tick fo' light lamp

fields.english: When a man sucks cane, he throws its peel on the ground.
fields.creole: When man suck cane, 'e mash 'e pilin' a-groun.'

fields.english: When a man wants to beat a dog, he finds a stick quickly.
fields.creole: When man wan' fo' beat daag, he 'fin' 'tick quick

fields.english: When my foot itches me, it's a sign that I'm going to walk.
fields.creole: When me foot itch me, a sign me go walk

fields.english: When my left hand itches, money is coming.
fields.creole: When me lef' han' 'cratch me, money a-come

fields.english: When my eyes are dancing, it's a sign I'm going to cry.
fields.creole: When me yeye a-dance, a sign me go cry

fields.english: When one tooth hurts you, all the rest are upset.
fields.creole: When one toot' hu't you, all de res' bex

fields.english: When the patwa (a type of fish) sees bait, it forgets that there's a hook at the bottom.
fields.creole: When patwa see bait, 'e fo'get say "'Ook de a-battam

fields.english: When a puppy gets plenty of milk, it turns up its nose at salt soup.
fields.creole: When puppy get plenty milk, he mek up he face 'pon sal' soup

fields.english: When it's drizzling, the devil and his wife are fighting for a ham bone.
fields.creole: When rain a-drizzle, debil an' he wife a-fight fo' ham bone

fields.english: When it's raining and the sun is shining, the devil is beating his wife.
fields.creole: When rain fall an' sun shining, debil licking he wife

fields.english: When a rat sees a cat, it never laughs.
fields.creole: When rat see cat, 'e nebbah laugh

fields.english: When the saucepan loses its cover, everyone peeps inside.
fields.creole: When saucepan loss he cobah, all man a-peep inside

fields.english: When a wound can't heal, one must sit down and bear it.
fields.creole: When sore can't get bettah, man gat fo' si' down bear am

fields.english: When the tiger gets old, the dog barks at it.
fields.creole: When ti'gah get ol', daag ba'k aftah am

fields.english: When the tiger is not there, the monkey gives the ball.
fields.creole: When tigal na deh, monkey gie ball

fields.english: When the tiger is sick, the deer lends him money.
fields.creole: When tigah sick, deer dun am fo' money

fields.english: When trouble comes, it doesn't blow its shell.
fields.creole: When trouble come, he no blow 'e shell

fields.english: When a white person gets into trouble, even a monkey's trousers will fit him.
fields.creole: When trouble ketch Bacra, monkey breeches fit am

fields.english: When trouble catches a man, he stands up and staggers; When trouble catches a woman, she sits down and considers.
fields.creole: When trouble ketch man, he 'tan' up an' 'taggah; When trouble ketch ooman, him si-down an' considah

fields.english: When two big bottles are on the table, the little one has no business there.
fields.creole: When two big bottle deh a-table, little wan no bu'iness

fields.english: When the barrel doesn't have a hoop, it must break down.
fields.creole: When tub na got hoople, he mus' bruck down

fields.english: When two dogs are fighting, the cat stands to one side.
fields.creole: When two daag get quarrel, Tom cat 'tan wan side

fields.english: When your brother is in trouble, don't laugh at him.
fields.creole: When you bruddah soak, don' laugh he

fields.english: When you're dead, you don't know, and when you know, you're already dead.
fields.creole: When you' dead you no sabby, an' when you sabby, you dead done

fields.english: When you get a donkey to ride, ride it for real.
fields.creole: When you get jackass fo' ride, ride am fo' true

fields.english: When you go into the bush, don't take the same road to come back.
fields.creole: When you go a-bush, no walk same road come back

fields.english: When you go to the countryside where they dance with one foot, you should also dance with one foot.
fields.creole: When you go a-country weh dem a-dance wid one foot, dance wid one foot too

fields.english: When you visit a friend's house, leave your appetite behind.
fields.creole: When you go a-frien' house, lef' you' 'tomach behin'

fields.english: When you have money, doors open; when you don't have, they shut.
fields.creole: When you gat money, doo' open; when you no gat, he shut

fields.english: When you have the devil to deal with, feed him with a long spoon.
fields.creole: When you hab de debil fo' deal wid, feed am wid long 'poon

fields.english: When your hand is yellow, dogs will make it so.
fields.creole: When you' han' yalla, daag mek so

fields.english: When you kill a bush cow, be careful how you carry it to the canoe.
fields.creole: When you kill comma, min' how you carry am a-canoe

fields.english: When you leave a wake, don't say "Good night".
fields.creole: When you lef' wake house, no say "Goo' night

fields.english: When you step on a dog, put on your shoes.
fields.creole: When you mash daag, put on you' shoes

fields.english: When your own louse bites you, it really bites you.
fields.creole: When you own louse bite you, he bite you fo' true
